1
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,074


2
00:02:41,828 --> 00:02:44,353
James Connors,
you are not Cab Calloway.

3
00:02:44,531 --> 00:02:46,658
We are trying to play
"The National Emblem."

4
00:02:46,833 --> 00:02:48,926
Not "My Heart Belongs to Daddy."

5
00:02:49,102 --> 00:02:50,330
Yes, ma'am.

6
00:02:50,837 --> 00:02:53,397
Well, I guess that's all we can do
for tonight.

7
00:02:53,573 --> 00:02:55,131
I think you'd better go home.

8
00:02:55,308 --> 00:02:56,832
Rehearsal's dismissed.

9
00:02:57,010 --> 00:02:59,444
Turn your music in to Willie.

10
00:03:00,246 --> 00:03:02,009
Willie. Here, Willie.

11
00:03:06,319 --> 00:03:10,346
You know, Jimmy, I'm getting to hate
these rehearsals. The same thing...

12
00:03:11,524 --> 00:03:13,082
...every time.
- Yeah.

13
00:03:13,259 --> 00:03:15,420
Would you like to stick around
and play records?

14
00:03:15,595 --> 00:03:18,428
I'd like to, but last time we did,
I didn't get home until 12.

15
00:03:18,598 --> 00:03:19,997
My dad was pretty burned up.

16
00:03:20,166 --> 00:03:22,293
We could knock out a couple
and get home early.

17
00:03:22,468 --> 00:03:26,063
- That's what you said last time.
- We were just practicing.

18
00:03:26,239 --> 00:03:28,366
But my folks think
I practice better at home.

19
00:03:28,541 --> 00:03:30,065
Anyway, Annie's waiting for me.

20
00:03:30,243 --> 00:03:32,108
- Oh, you're dead.
- Yeah. Good night.

21
00:03:32,278 --> 00:03:34,303
Booper, like to try
a little classical swing?

22
00:03:34,480 --> 00:03:38,314
Can't do it. My family's out of sympathy
with these night sessions you been having.

23
00:03:38,484 --> 00:03:41,146
- See you tomorrow, Jimmy.
- So long, Boop.

24
00:04:37,744 --> 00:04:39,075
Is that you, Jimmy?

25
00:04:40,079 --> 00:04:41,341
Yes, Mom.

26
00:04:41,514 --> 00:04:43,846
What time is it, dear?

27
00:04:44,117 --> 00:04:46,449
Gosh, Mom, I don't know.

28
00:04:46,619 --> 00:04:49,315
It must be close to 11.

29
00:04:55,295 --> 00:04:57,388
Good night, son.

30
00:04:58,164 --> 00:04:59,756
Good night, Mom.

31
00:05:30,496 --> 00:05:31,963
- How was I doing?
- Swell.

32
00:05:32,131 --> 00:05:34,531
Say, I'm glad you're here, Mary.
I wanna talk to you.

33
00:05:34,701 --> 00:05:36,191
- Okay.
- Well...

34
00:05:36,369 --> 00:05:38,769
You know, I don't go around
steaming people up.

35
00:05:38,938 --> 00:05:41,168
Oh, no, of course not.

36
00:05:41,341 --> 00:05:44,902
Remember once I told you that someday
we might have our own dance orchestra?

37
00:05:45,078 --> 00:05:46,568
- Yes.
- Well, the dog is barking.

38
00:05:46,746 --> 00:05:49,681
- What do you mean?
- I've been thinking it over in my mind.

39
00:05:49,849 --> 00:05:52,875
A fellow doesn't wanna play
with a broken-down brass band anymore.

40
00:05:53,052 --> 00:05:54,679
You know, the same:

41
00:05:55,755 --> 00:05:57,052
He gets tired of that.

42
00:05:57,223 --> 00:06:00,192
Instead of the school having a band
play a concert once a year...

43
00:06:00,360 --> 00:06:03,090
...why, we could have our own
great modern dance orchestra.

44
00:06:03,262 --> 00:06:04,752
We've got everything right here.

45
00:06:04,931 --> 00:06:08,162
We've got the brass, the piano,
the reeds and you and...

46
00:06:08,334 --> 00:06:10,427
- Me?
- Sure. You could handle all the vocals.

47
00:06:10,837 --> 00:06:12,498
Oh, that sounds wonderful, Jimmy.

48
00:06:12,672 --> 00:06:14,799
It is. We could make
our own arrangements...

49
00:06:14,974 --> 00:06:17,306
...and specialties
and play for all the dances.

50
00:06:17,477 --> 00:06:19,707
We could put Riverwood High School
on the map.

51
00:06:19,879 --> 00:06:22,313
Now, all we gotta do
is to get the school behind us.

52
00:06:22,482 --> 00:06:24,643
Do you think we could sell the idea
to Mr. Judd?

53
00:06:24,817 --> 00:06:26,944
- Mr. Judd, the principal?
- Yeah.

54
00:06:27,120 --> 00:06:28,849
I thought the last time you saw him...

55
00:06:29,021 --> 00:06:31,251
Well, I don't think
he'd hold my past against me.

56
00:06:31,424 --> 00:06:32,982
This is something big.

57
00:06:33,159 --> 00:06:34,854
Will you go down to see him with me?

58
00:06:35,027 --> 00:06:36,585
- Maybe tonight?
- Sure, I'll go.

59
00:06:36,763 --> 00:06:38,958
- It's a date.
- All right.

60
00:06:46,873 --> 00:06:50,240
- Be right there, Jimmy.
- All right, Mary.

61
00:06:55,181 --> 00:06:56,409
I won't be gone long.

62
00:06:56,582 --> 00:06:57,810
- Hello.
- Hello, Mrs. Holden.

63
00:06:57,984 --> 00:07:00,544
I told mother about the band.
She thinks it's wonderful.

64
00:07:00,720 --> 00:07:02,688
- You do?
- Of course. I think it's splendid.

65
00:07:02,855 --> 00:07:04,982
Doesn't your mother think so too?

66
00:07:05,691 --> 00:07:08,558
Yes, ma'am. She thinks it's great.

67
00:07:10,196 --> 00:07:13,222
Well, I guess we'd better be going.
Good night, Mother.

68
00:07:13,399 --> 00:07:14,661
Good night, Mrs. Holden.

69
00:07:15,001 --> 00:07:18,061
- Good luck with Mr. Judd.
- Thanks.

70
00:07:25,077 --> 00:07:27,739
That was a fib,
what you said about your mother.

71
00:07:27,914 --> 00:07:30,246
- Yeah.
- Why'd you say it?

72
00:07:30,416 --> 00:07:33,044
- I don't know.
- You didn't even tell your mother.

73
00:07:33,219 --> 00:07:35,449
- No.
- Why?

74
00:07:35,621 --> 00:07:38,317
Well, I guess I'm afraid to.

75
00:07:38,491 --> 00:07:40,391
Afraid to tell your mother?

76
00:07:40,560 --> 00:07:42,619
Mary, it isn't as easy as you think.

77
00:07:42,795 --> 00:07:46,595
It's not just telling her that we're gonna
have a band, lot of fun, lot of laughs.

78
00:07:46,766 --> 00:07:48,199
You see, I've gotta tell her...

79
00:07:48,367 --> 00:07:52,360
I've gotta tell her that this is it, music.
It's my future. It's the thing I want most.

80
00:07:52,538 --> 00:07:55,006
- Maybe she'd understand.
- No, I don't think she would.

81
00:07:55,174 --> 00:07:57,642
She wants me to be a doctor like Dad.

82
00:07:57,810 --> 00:08:01,177
But, Mary, look at me.
Do I look like a doctor?

83
00:08:04,217 --> 00:08:06,481
- No, I guess you don't.
- No, of course I don't.

84
00:08:06,652 --> 00:08:09,678
But ever since I can remember,
she's always talked to me about it.

85
00:08:09,856 --> 00:08:13,053
Well, I've agreed with her because it...
I saw that it made her happy.

86
00:08:13,226 --> 00:08:14,750
But now I can't even do that.

87
00:08:14,927 --> 00:08:17,293
Well, Jimmy, are you sure
you wanna be a drummer?

88
00:08:17,463 --> 00:08:19,829
Mary, I was never more sure
of anything in my life.

89
00:08:19,999 --> 00:08:22,695
You've got to be really sure.
Why don't you wait and see...

90
00:08:22,869 --> 00:08:25,633
...what Mr. Judd says
about you organizing this school band?

91
00:08:25,805 --> 00:08:29,172
If he says it's all right, and the first
school dance is a big success...

92
00:08:29,342 --> 00:08:32,539
...and you know that that's what
you wanna do, go to her and tell her.

93
00:08:32,712 --> 00:08:33,940
She'll understand.

94
00:08:34,113 --> 00:08:37,913
Because she'd realize
that your ambition is strong and sincere.

95
00:08:38,084 --> 00:08:40,712
Oh, mothers are like that, Jimmy.

96
00:08:40,887 --> 00:08:44,789
Gee, I never thought of it
that way before.

97
00:08:45,892 --> 00:08:47,757
But you're right, Mary, and I'll do it.

98
00:08:47,927 --> 00:08:49,861
Oh, you know, you're so wonderful.

99
00:08:50,029 --> 00:08:53,157
It's a great comfort to have somebody
you can tell your troubles to.

100
00:08:53,332 --> 00:08:55,800
You're always wonderful
about putting me on the track.

101
00:08:55,968 --> 00:08:57,333
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

102
00:08:57,503 --> 00:09:01,906
You know, you're gonna make
some man a fine wife.

103
00:09:02,074 --> 00:09:03,974
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

104
00:09:04,143 --> 00:09:06,941
And, well, I'm gonna envy the guy
that gets you too.

105
00:09:07,113 --> 00:09:08,478
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

106
00:09:08,648 --> 00:09:11,583
And, Mary, I'll never forget
what a great pal you've been to me.

107
00:09:11,751 --> 00:09:12,979
- Yeah?
- Yeah!

108
00:09:13,152 --> 00:09:15,643
Straight from the shoulder, a real pal.

109
00:09:15,821 --> 00:09:18,551
- Reminds me of a song.
- What song?

110
00:09:18,724 --> 00:09:22,057
"Oh! What A Pal Was Mary."

111
00:09:22,461 --> 00:09:24,258
Yeah!

112
00:09:26,165 --> 00:09:27,154
Yeah.

113
00:09:28,968 --> 00:09:32,131
Jimmy, the band
has been a big disappointment.

114
00:09:32,305 --> 00:09:34,967
- Are the boys losing interest?
- No, sir, not in the music.

115
00:09:35,141 --> 00:09:37,336
There are awfully fine musicians
in that outfit.

116
00:09:37,510 --> 00:09:40,104
They're just not interested
in the stuff they're playing.

117
00:09:40,279 --> 00:09:44,272
When you start playing anything,
you've gotta be hopping inside.

118
00:09:44,450 --> 00:09:46,714
Oh, it's wonderful for parades
and Memorial Day...

119
00:09:46,886 --> 00:09:50,151
...but people don't wanna sit around
and listen to that stuff anymore.

120
00:09:50,323 --> 00:09:54,453
Jimmy, I've been giving it a lot
of thought lately, and I'm glad you told me.

121
00:09:54,627 --> 00:09:57,118
The band has cost the school
a lot of money.

122
00:09:57,296 --> 00:10:00,788
Maybe we better disorganize it
and call the whole thing off.

123
00:10:00,967 --> 00:10:03,367
We're already enough in debt.

124
00:10:04,036 --> 00:10:06,561
Mr. Judd, you just give me 60 seconds
of your time...

125
00:10:06,739 --> 00:10:08,969
...and I'll brush that burden
off your shoulders.

126
00:10:09,141 --> 00:10:11,109
Go ahead, Jimmy. It would be a pleasure.

127
00:10:11,277 --> 00:10:14,337
Well, I've been talking to the fellows
and we'd like to organize...

128
00:10:14,513 --> 00:10:16,378
...our own dance band.
- Dance orchestra?

129
00:10:16,549 --> 00:10:20,417
Certainly. Instead of a brass band,
we'd like to have a modern dance orchestra.

130
00:10:20,586 --> 00:10:25,114
Let us go ahead and form this band and give
a high school dance instead of the concert.

131
00:10:25,291 --> 00:10:28,556
And I'll guarantee you that within one night,
we'll wipe out that debt.

132
00:10:28,728 --> 00:10:31,697
I know it. I've been thinking it over
for a long time.

133
00:10:31,864 --> 00:10:35,061
If we don't bring in as many people
at the dance as at the concerts...

134
00:10:35,234 --> 00:10:37,998
...in the past 10 years,
we'll forget about the whole thing.

135
00:10:38,170 --> 00:10:42,334
Just a minute. You're going to organize
a dance orchestra, ready to play...

136
00:10:42,508 --> 00:10:44,908
Not only are we gonna have
a great dance orchestra...

137
00:10:45,077 --> 00:10:47,238
...but we're also gonna have
a great singer too.

138
00:10:47,413 --> 00:10:49,847
Oh, I see.

139
00:10:51,684 --> 00:10:54,551
- You're going to arrange the whole thing?
- Yes, sir.

140
00:10:54,720 --> 00:10:58,315
Publicity, selling tickets...

141
00:10:58,491 --> 00:11:00,721
...paying off the debt of the band.

142
00:11:00,893 --> 00:11:03,953
The whole thing, all in three weeks?

143
00:11:04,130 --> 00:11:07,156
- In a breeze.
- In a breeze?

144
00:11:08,034 --> 00:11:11,970
You've taken on a pretty large order,
Jimmy. I don't believe you can do it.

145
00:11:12,138 --> 00:11:14,402
Oh, he can do it.
I know he can do it, Mr. Judd.

146
00:11:14,573 --> 00:11:18,942
I'm sure I can do it, if you'll only
give me the chance, Mr. Judd.

147
00:11:21,580 --> 00:11:24,378
All right. I'll buy the first ticket.

148
00:11:24,550 --> 00:11:27,144
Oh, thanks, Mr. Judd.

149
00:11:29,288 --> 00:11:32,780
Mary, the principal shook hands with me.

150
00:11:34,460 --> 00:11:36,360
We certainly slipped it to him all right.

151
00:11:36,529 --> 00:11:38,520
- We certainly did.
- There's a great old guy.

152
00:11:38,698 --> 00:11:41,098
- He's a great old guy.
- Vision. That's what he's got.

153
00:11:41,267 --> 00:11:43,258
There's a man that can see
over the transom.

154
00:11:43,436 --> 00:11:45,461
- Yes sir, he's gonna go places.
- He sure is.

155
00:11:45,638 --> 00:11:47,003
- You know what that was?
- What?

156
00:11:47,173 --> 00:11:50,199
A springboard. He just launched
the biggest ship that ever sailed.

157
00:11:50,376 --> 00:11:53,368
- You're absolutely right. Okay.
- Let's take a short cut.

158
00:11:56,482 --> 00:11:58,006
You know, I misjudged that man.

159
00:11:58,184 --> 00:12:01,585
- Heart, that's what he's got. A lot of heart.
- Here, I'll help you.

160
00:12:01,754 --> 00:12:04,780
- Something's been troubling me lately.
- What?

161
00:12:05,524 --> 00:12:09,893
Do you think "our Love Affair"
has enough punch in it?

162
00:12:10,296 --> 00:12:11,854
"Our Love Affair."

163
00:12:12,031 --> 00:12:14,124
Oh, well,
now that you mentioned it, Jimmy...

164
00:12:14,300 --> 00:12:16,165
Because I've got
a new arrangement on it.

165
00:12:16,335 --> 00:12:18,929
Oh, it's a dynamite love song
just made-to-order for you.

166
00:12:19,105 --> 00:12:20,732
I'll play it.

167
00:12:21,073 --> 00:12:23,701
Wait until you get a load of this intro.

168
00:12:23,876 --> 00:12:27,107
I've got some chords
that are really out of this world.

169
00:12:27,379 --> 00:12:28,903
Listen.

170
00:12:30,616 --> 00:12:33,016
It starts off a little flairy.

171
00:12:33,185 --> 00:12:35,085
Are you listening to me?

172
00:12:35,387 --> 00:12:38,481
Then it softens down here.
It's violins, you know?

173
00:12:38,657 --> 00:12:42,559
Then the orchestra sneaks back in
for the vocal.

174
00:12:43,095 --> 00:12:49,034
<i>Our love affair will be such fun</i>

175
00:12:49,201 --> 00:12:54,764
<i>We'll be the envy of everyone</i>

176
00:12:55,141 --> 00:13:00,602
<i>Those famous lovers
We'll make them forget</i>

177
00:13:01,113 --> 00:13:06,608
<i>From Adam and Eve
To Scarlett and Rhett</i>

178
00:13:06,786 --> 00:13:07,980
Flutes and oboes.

179
00:13:08,154 --> 00:13:14,684
<i>When youth has had its merry fling</i>

180
00:13:14,860 --> 00:13:21,265
<i>We'll spend our evenings remembering</i>

181
00:13:21,433 --> 00:13:27,065
<i>Two happy people
Who say on the square</i>

182
00:13:27,239 --> 00:13:28,331
With fiddles.

183
00:13:28,507 --> 00:13:36,539
<i>Isn't ours a lovely love affair?</i>

184
00:13:40,319 --> 00:13:41,547
Come on, sit down. Try it.

185
00:13:41,720 --> 00:13:44,883
Are you sure you want me to sing
with the band? You're not just...

186
00:13:45,057 --> 00:13:46,422
of course not, we need you.

187
00:13:46,592 --> 00:13:48,958
You're as important to me
as the brass section.

188
00:13:49,128 --> 00:13:51,892
- That's pretty important.
- Try the verse.

189
00:13:52,064 --> 00:13:58,469
<i>Here we are
Two very bewildered people</i>

190
00:13:59,438 --> 00:14:05,741
<i>Here we are
Two babes that are lost in the wood</i>

191
00:14:05,911 --> 00:14:12,316
<i>We're not quite certain
What has happened to us</i>

192
00:14:12,484 --> 00:14:17,888
<i>This lovely thing that's so marvelous</i>

193
00:14:18,057 --> 00:14:20,025
<i>But right from here</i>

194
00:14:20,192 --> 00:14:26,495
<i>The future looks awfully good</i>

195
00:14:27,433 --> 00:14:34,168
<i>Our love affair
Was meant to be</i>

196
00:14:34,340 --> 00:14:37,867
<i>It's me for you, dear</i>

197
00:14:38,043 --> 00:14:41,444
<i>And you for me</i>

198
00:14:41,614 --> 00:14:44,947
<i>We'll fuss, we'll quarrel</i>

199
00:14:45,117 --> 00:14:48,245
<i>And tears start to brew</i>

200
00:14:48,420 --> 00:14:51,583
<i>But after the tears</i>

201
00:14:51,757 --> 00:14:56,490
<i>Our love will smile through</i>

202
00:14:56,662 --> 00:15:00,689
<i>I'm sure that I</i>

203
00:15:00,866 --> 00:15:04,267
<i>Could never hide</i>

204
00:15:04,436 --> 00:15:06,996
<i>The thrill I get</i>

205
00:15:07,172 --> 00:15:11,472
<i>When you're by my side</i>

206
00:15:11,644 --> 00:15:15,045
<i>And when we're older</i>

207
00:15:15,214 --> 00:15:19,116
<i>We'll proudly declare</i>

208
00:15:19,285 --> 00:15:28,921
<i>Wasn't ours a lovely love affair?</i>

209
00:15:30,796 --> 00:15:36,462
<i>I'll learn to bake a chocolate cake</i>

210
00:15:36,635 --> 00:15:43,131
<i>The kind of cake mother used to make</i>

211
00:15:43,309 --> 00:15:46,767
You hungry? Come on, let's go see
if we can find some of that cake.

212
00:15:46,946 --> 00:15:48,538
Swell.

213
00:15:48,714 --> 00:15:52,047
I hope there's some left,
if Daddy hasn't eaten it all up.

214
00:15:55,587 --> 00:15:59,956
You know, Mary,
I'd never be satisfied with a small band.

215
00:16:00,125 --> 00:16:03,561
I want a great big one. A symphony.

216
00:16:03,729 --> 00:16:05,754
Why, I wanna make American music...

217
00:16:05,931 --> 00:16:08,195
...just as important
as any other country's music.

218
00:16:08,634 --> 00:16:09,726
Look at George Gershwin.

219
00:16:09,902 --> 00:16:13,167
Why, his music is as good
as Beethoven or Bach, better maybe.

220
00:16:13,339 --> 00:16:15,307
Best of all, it's American.

221
00:16:16,275 --> 00:16:18,140
You like grapes and strawberries?

222
00:16:19,611 --> 00:16:22,774
Can you imagine me conducting
a concert in Carnegie Hall?

223
00:16:22,948 --> 00:16:24,779
Oh, boy, what a thrill.

224
00:16:24,950 --> 00:16:26,349
On my left, I have 50 fiddles.

225
00:16:26,652 --> 00:16:29,280
Fifty? That's a lot of strings.

226
00:16:33,792 --> 00:16:37,387
And on my right,
I'd have the violas and the cellos.

227
00:16:37,997 --> 00:16:39,794
Oh, wonderful.

228
00:16:41,333 --> 00:16:45,235
And right in front of me,
I'd have the saxes and the clarinets.

229
00:16:47,706 --> 00:16:50,266
You know, the woodwind
is the real body to an orchestra.

230
00:16:50,442 --> 00:16:52,706
Right in back of them,
I'd have the brass section.

231
00:16:56,949 --> 00:16:59,577
Over in the back,
I'd have the bass fiddles. Ten of them.

232
00:16:59,752 --> 00:17:03,210
- Ten?
- Sure, you gotta have a good beat.

233
00:17:04,556 --> 00:17:07,821
Then I'd have the drums
