be careful how you climb that ladder.

464
00:37:09,594 --> 00:37:11,824
Because that's very important, too.

465
00:37:11,996 --> 00:37:14,191
I will, Mom. I will.

466
00:37:14,365 --> 00:37:18,665
And when I get there, nothing they could
cook up would be too good for you.

467
00:37:20,671 --> 00:37:23,799
- You know what, Mom?
- What, Jimmy?

468
00:37:25,443 --> 00:37:27,968
I'm gonna make you a queen.

469
00:37:30,615 --> 00:37:34,051
Wait a minute, you're eating too fast.
You're gonna get sick.

470
00:37:34,218 --> 00:37:38,211
- Yes, you are, you darling.
- Hey, Mary!

471
00:37:38,756 --> 00:37:41,919
Mary. Hey, Mary.

472
00:37:46,931 --> 00:37:49,331
Give me a mountain,
I wanna crush it into a molehill.

473
00:37:49,500 --> 00:37:52,196
- Who's been feeding you vitamins?
- I was worried about Mom.

474
00:37:52,370 --> 00:37:54,770
We had a long talk
and everything's fixed, like that.

475
00:37:54,939 --> 00:37:56,133
That's wonderful, Jimmy.

476
00:37:56,307 --> 00:37:58,901
I got the greatest news
since the invention of the wheel.

477
00:37:59,076 --> 00:38:01,169
- You have?
- I'm gonna give it to you straight.

478
00:38:01,345 --> 00:38:05,247
I found this in the newspaper. It's been
burning a hole in my pocket. Listen.

479
00:38:05,416 --> 00:38:07,884
"Paul Whiteman, number one band leader,
now on tour...

480
00:38:08,052 --> 00:38:11,317
...through the cities of the country,
decided, due to great interest...

481
00:38:11,489 --> 00:38:13,650
...among the youth of America
in modern music...

482
00:38:13,824 --> 00:38:17,225
...to give auditions to high school
dance orchestras in various cities."

483
00:38:17,395 --> 00:38:18,623
This is the important part.

484
00:38:18,796 --> 00:38:22,357
"Mr. Whiteman's final selection will be
guest-starred on his radio program...

485
00:38:22,533 --> 00:38:23,898
...on June 29th from Chicago."

486
00:38:24,068 --> 00:38:26,468
- That is something.
- Just think what it mould mean...

487
00:38:26,637 --> 00:38:28,161
...if our band made that program.

488
00:38:28,339 --> 00:38:31,467
It'd put Riverwood High School
on the front page of every newspaper.

489
00:38:31,642 --> 00:38:32,631
You bet it would.

490
00:38:32,810 --> 00:38:36,405
Suppose we got to Chicago on the 28th
and we gave Mr. Whiteman the audition.

491
00:38:36,580 --> 00:38:39,481
We could stay until the next day
and play on the radio program.

492
00:38:39,650 --> 00:38:42,346
It would cost a fortune
to get that whole band to Chicago.

493
00:38:42,520 --> 00:38:43,748
No, I've figured it out.

494
00:38:43,921 --> 00:38:47,118
To get the band there and back by bus
and two days in Chicago...

495
00:38:47,291 --> 00:38:48,553
...it'll cost about $200.

496
00:38:48,726 --> 00:38:50,023
That's if nobody eats heavy.

497
00:38:50,194 --> 00:38:52,924
Oh, Jimmy, that's an awful lot of money
even if we have it.

498
00:38:53,097 --> 00:38:57,124
- Yeah, it is quite a bundle.
- But it's not impossible.

499
00:38:57,301 --> 00:38:59,064
When's bank night?

500
00:38:59,804 --> 00:39:01,533
You're pressing.

501
00:39:03,708 --> 00:39:08,304
Say, suppose we went over
and we had a little talk with...

502
00:39:08,479 --> 00:39:11,243
- Mr. Judd.
- The school board will do anything he says.

503
00:39:11,415 --> 00:39:13,747
- He was crazy about our band.
- We out to get him...

504
00:39:13,918 --> 00:39:16,887
...while he's in a good humor.
- What are we waiting for?

505
00:39:17,054 --> 00:39:21,650
I'm sorry. And I'm still sorrier
to have to disappoint you.

506
00:39:21,826 --> 00:39:24,420
But I couldn't give my consent.

507
00:39:24,595 --> 00:39:28,895
It would be impossible for the school
to finance a venture of this kind.

508
00:39:29,066 --> 00:39:31,261
But, if you'd only tell them
what it would mean.

509
00:39:31,435 --> 00:39:34,302
The publicity for Riverwood High School
and how big it was.

510
00:39:34,472 --> 00:39:38,431
That's one of the troubles.
I'm afraid they think it's too big already.

511
00:39:38,609 --> 00:39:40,076
I might as well tell you, Jimmy.

512
00:39:40,244 --> 00:39:43,179
There have been complaints
from parents of the boys in the band.

513
00:39:43,347 --> 00:39:45,645
Interfering with studies, late hours.

514
00:39:45,816 --> 00:39:49,582
No, I'll have to veto this, Jimmy.
Definitely.

515
00:39:50,388 --> 00:39:52,788
Well, I'm sorry
to have bothered you, Mr. Judd.

516
00:39:52,957 --> 00:39:54,891
That perfectly all right, Jimmy.

517
00:39:55,059 --> 00:39:57,584
You come to see me any time you want.

518
00:39:59,163 --> 00:40:00,824
- Goodbye, Mr. Judd.
- Goodbye, Mary.

519
00:40:00,998 --> 00:40:04,456
- Jimmy.
- Goodbye. Thanks.

520
00:40:04,635 --> 00:40:06,535
Well, he was nice about it, anyway.

521
00:40:06,704 --> 00:40:10,003
Yeah, but a kind heart
will never get us to Chicago.

522
00:40:11,342 --> 00:40:13,902
Well, Phil, there's more than one way
of spinning a top.

523
00:40:14,078 --> 00:40:16,444
- Yeah.
- Maybe the school board is content...

524
00:40:16,614 --> 00:40:20,414
...with having Riverwood remain a little
red dot on an auto map, but not me.

525
00:40:20,584 --> 00:40:21,949
We packed them in last night.

526
00:40:22,119 --> 00:40:24,713
We gave them a good time
after we got them in, didn't we?

527
00:40:24,889 --> 00:40:26,823
- Yeah.
- All right.

528
00:40:26,991 --> 00:40:30,757
I've been thinking ever since we left
Mr. Judd's house how we can raise $200.

529
00:40:30,928 --> 00:40:32,452
- Yeah.
- We've got a terrific band.

530
00:40:32,630 --> 00:40:34,325
It's hot merchandise.

531
00:40:34,498 --> 00:40:37,695
Oh, we'll get to Chicago if we have to
crawl on our hands and knees...

532
00:40:37,868 --> 00:40:39,836
...and blow out every lamp on the way.

533
00:40:40,004 --> 00:40:42,097
I think Annie's good and sore.

534
00:40:42,273 --> 00:40:45,037
Yeah, she's really burned up, all right.

535
00:40:45,209 --> 00:40:48,610
Annie. Annie. Annie!
Is that all I get out of you is Annie?

536
00:40:48,779 --> 00:40:50,679
- Aren't you interested in the band?
- Sure.

537
00:40:50,848 --> 00:40:54,409
Don't you realize we only got six weeks
to raise the money to get to Chicago?

538
00:40:54,585 --> 00:40:58,282
This is terrific, there's bands from
all over the country. This isn't baby talk.

539
00:40:58,456 --> 00:41:01,425
- I'm with you, all the way. You know that.
- All right, all right.

540
00:41:01,592 --> 00:41:04,891
So we've got to raise $200.
How we gonna do it?

541
00:41:06,797 --> 00:41:08,992
How about some punchboards?

542
00:41:10,668 --> 00:41:12,863
Punchboards, sure, sure.

543
00:41:13,037 --> 00:41:15,301
- And we'll give Annie away as a prize.
- Yeah.

544
00:41:15,473 --> 00:41:18,465
- Lf you're gonna be a wise guy.
- Oh, I was only kidding, Phil.

545
00:41:18,642 --> 00:41:21,270
I mean, we got to keep in there punching.

546
00:41:21,445 --> 00:41:24,380
Wait a minute. Why couldn't we
make a deal with the Elks Club...

547
00:41:24,548 --> 00:41:26,573
...to give a dance
at their Milk Fund Bazaar?

548
00:41:26,750 --> 00:41:31,312
<i>- Well, it's only a month away.
- Oh, they don't give dances at any...</i>

549
00:41:34,525 --> 00:41:37,494
Say, that's not a bad idea.

550
00:41:37,661 --> 00:41:40,186
We could put on our own show.
That'd be different.

551
00:41:40,364 --> 00:41:43,265
We could make up our own specialties,
sketches, dance routines.

552
00:41:43,434 --> 00:41:44,924
Great, I like it already.

553
00:41:45,102 --> 00:41:47,229
Say, what's the number one Elk?

554
00:41:47,404 --> 00:41:51,500
- Who is he? The whatchamacallit?
- Mr. Mollison, and he owes my dad money.

555
00:41:51,675 --> 00:41:53,905
- That's our man.
- I'll get after it right away.

556
00:41:54,078 --> 00:41:57,138
Mr. Mollison? Gotta make a list
down here, we gotta get costumes.

557
00:41:57,314 --> 00:41:59,680
Cot Mollison. Mollison.

558
00:41:59,850 --> 00:42:01,977
- You know what, Jimmy?
- What?

559
00:42:02,152 --> 00:42:04,643
I think I ought to call Annie.

560
00:42:06,123 --> 00:42:08,591
You're still making valentines again.

561
00:42:08,759 --> 00:42:11,353
When Annie's sore at me,
it throws me all off key.

562
00:42:11,529 --> 00:42:14,191
I just can't stand talking to a guy
with a one-track mind.

563
00:42:14,365 --> 00:42:18,165
Well, wait'll you're in love with somebody.
You'll know what I'm going through.

564
00:42:18,335 --> 00:42:22,203
Women to me are just people.

565
00:42:30,347 --> 00:42:34,147
- Oh, Miss Hodges, I'm sorry to disturb you.
- It's perfectly all right, Mr. Judd.

566
00:42:34,318 --> 00:42:37,219
I'd like you to meet a new student,
Barbara Frances Morgan.

567
00:42:37,388 --> 00:42:40,824
- How do you do, Barbara Frances?
- I'm delighted to know you, Miss Hodges.

568
00:42:41,091 --> 00:42:44,458
My, what a nice, bright classroom.

569
00:42:44,762 --> 00:42:47,788
Mr. Morgan wants Barbara Frances
to finish out the term here.

570
00:42:47,965 --> 00:42:50,866
- I've selected this as her homeroom.
- We're happy to have her.

571
00:42:51,035 --> 00:42:55,165
I'm sure you won't have any difficulty
getting into the swing of things.

572
00:42:55,339 --> 00:42:56,966
I'm sure I won't.

573
00:42:57,141 --> 00:42:59,132
- Thank you, Miss Hodges.
- Don't mention it.

574
00:42:59,310 --> 00:43:02,245
Now, let me see.
Where shall we put you?

575
00:43:06,617 --> 00:43:09,450
Oh, yes. Suppose you sit
in that empty chair over there.

576
00:43:09,620 --> 00:43:11,053
Thank you.

577
00:43:11,755 --> 00:43:14,315
And if you're happy there,
you may keep it permanently.

578
00:43:14,491 --> 00:43:16,891
I'm sure I will be.

579
00:43:28,105 --> 00:43:30,903
- She's touched it up.
- Yeah.

580
00:43:36,947 --> 00:43:40,883
Oh, James, I wonder if you'd take
Barbara Frances to the supply room...

581
00:43:41,051 --> 00:43:45,545
...and help her with her text books.
- Would it inconvenience you terribly?

582
00:43:45,723 --> 00:43:49,284
No, not at all.

583
00:43:53,397 --> 00:43:55,331
Have you traveled very much?

584
00:43:55,499 --> 00:43:58,127
- Me, travel?
- Yes, travel.

585
00:43:58,302 --> 00:44:00,065
Well, a little.

586
00:44:01,338 --> 00:44:05,001
That is, my uncle took me to Chicago
three years ago to see the World Series.

587
00:44:05,175 --> 00:44:07,666
Oh, no. I mean the continent.

588
00:44:09,613 --> 00:44:13,310
- Which one?
- Oh, you must see the Riviera.

589
00:44:14,284 --> 00:44:19,153
- Must I?
- Cannes, Nice, San Raphael, Juan-les-Pins.

590
00:44:19,323 --> 00:44:24,351
- Juan-les-pins is simply wild.
- It is, huh?

591
00:44:25,195 --> 00:44:29,097
I met the most wonderful man there.
Almost too beautiful.

592
00:44:29,266 --> 00:44:32,599
But he turned out to be a duke,
and you know what they are.

593
00:44:32,770 --> 00:44:36,763
Yeah, yeah,
you've got to watch those dukes.

594
00:44:37,708 --> 00:44:40,506
Oh, there goes the bell.
We're gonna be late for our classes.

595
00:44:40,678 --> 00:44:45,911
Oh, dear. And we were just getting
to know each other.

596
00:44:51,955 --> 00:44:53,752
You're cute.

597
00:45:01,165 --> 00:45:02,757
Are you going right home now, Mary?

598
00:45:02,933 --> 00:45:05,493
No, honey,
I have to work at the library today.

599
00:45:05,669 --> 00:45:07,432
I had a talk with my dad
this noontime.

600
00:45:07,604 --> 00:45:10,402
He thinks he can fix an appointment
with Mr. Mollison for us.

601
00:45:10,574 --> 00:45:12,474
He can? Oh, that's swell.
Good work, Phil.

602
00:45:12,643 --> 00:45:17,376
- Well, I've got to meet Annie. So long.
- Annie, so long.

603
00:45:18,482 --> 00:45:22,282
Oh, Jimmy, Jimmy. Looking for me?

604
00:45:23,053 --> 00:45:24,714
Well, no, not exactly.

605
00:45:24,888 --> 00:45:27,880
- Come on, jump in. I'll drive you home.
- Thanks anyway, Barbara.

606
00:45:28,058 --> 00:45:30,618
- I don't think l...
- oh, come on, jump in.

607
00:45:31,295 --> 00:45:32,762
Stuck.

608
00:45:33,097 --> 00:45:35,759
Hey, Jimmy,
how's the weather down there?

609
00:45:35,933 --> 00:45:37,867
Get a load of that.

610
00:45:39,036 --> 00:45:41,937
Say, that Barbara Frances
doesn't waste any time, does she?

611
00:45:42,106 --> 00:45:44,700
How about Jimmy? He's doing all right.

612
00:45:45,175 --> 00:45:48,235
Just give me the word, Mary,
and I'll slug him.

613
00:45:54,618 --> 00:45:58,349
Oh, the county fair, wonderful.

614
00:45:59,389 --> 00:46:04,759
- The fair, are you going?
- Oh, yeah, sure. I never miss the fair.

615
00:46:04,928 --> 00:46:07,453
- I wish I could go.
- Well, why can't you?

616
00:46:07,631 --> 00:46:13,092
Well, I don't know many young people,
and a girl can't very well go there alone.

617
00:46:13,370 --> 00:46:16,567
I wouldn't worry about that
if I were you. Somebody will ask you.

618
00:46:16,740 --> 00:46:19,834
Oh, Jimmy, isn't that sweet of you?

619
00:46:20,310 --> 00:46:22,676
Oh, no, no, well, I can't...

620
00:46:22,846 --> 00:46:27,010
You're really a dear.
You have the cutest way of saying things.

621
00:46:42,232 --> 00:46:45,292
- Hello, Mary.
- Hello, Jimmy.

622
00:46:46,937 --> 00:46:49,735
- What you doing?
- Just putting these books away.

623
00:46:49,907 --> 00:46:52,398
Gosh, there's an awful lot of them,
aren't there?

624
00:46:52,576 --> 00:46:55,670
- Yeah.
- You read them all?

625
00:46:56,013 --> 00:46:57,947
Only up to here.

626
00:46:59,249 --> 00:47:01,877
<i>Mary, about that fair...</i>

627
00:47:03,053 --> 00:47:04,384
What about it?

628
00:47:04,555 --> 00:47:06,216
Well, I thought that you and I...

629
00:47:06,390 --> 00:47:10,383
...we had an understanding
that we were going together to the fair.

630
00:47:11,028 --> 00:47:14,896
<i>Well, I got myself all tied up and...</i>

631
00:47:19,336 --> 00:47:23,602
oh, there was really no definite
understanding that we were going together.

632
00:47:24,074 --> 00:47:25,701
Besides, I'm pretty busy.

633
00:47:25,876 --> 00:47:30,336
And fairs, they're just a bunch of livestock
and a merry-go-round.

634
00:47:30,514 --> 00:47:34,575
I've seen all that.
Besides, they're really for children.

635
00:47:34,751 --> 00:47:36,912
Oh, you wouldn't like
anything like that, huh?

636
00:47:37,087 --> 00:47:39,055
Oh, I'd like it all right.

637
00:47:39,223 --> 00:47:43,592
But there are a lot more important things
in life than going to the fairs with people.

638
00:47:43,760 --> 00:47:46,092
Sure, sure, sure, there are.

639
00:47:46,396 --> 00:47:49,763
I'd better get going. I just thought
I'd drop in and explain it to you.

640
00:47:49,933 --> 00:47:54,165
- I knew that you'd understand.
- Oh, sure, I understand.

641
00:47:54,338 --> 00:47:56,636
You can always count on me, Jimmy.

642
00:47:56,807 --> 00:47:58,900
Just the same
as you could your own cousin.

643
00:47:59,076 --> 00:48:01,670
Yeah, and I appreciate it, too.

644
00:48:05,482 --> 00:48:09,646
Well, well, so long.

645
00:48:11,722 --> 00:48:15,624
So long, pal.

646
00:48:23,634 --> 00:48:27,263
<i>Mary, where can I find
a copy of Romeo and Juliet?</i>

647
00:48:27,437 --> 00:48:30,338
Back there with the rest
of the Shakespeare, on the last shelf.

648
00:48:30,507 --> 00:48:31,769
Thanks.

649
00:48:32,209 --> 00:48:34,370
<i>Where's Antony and Cleopatra?</i>

650
00:48:34,544 --> 00:48:37,809
<i>Right back there,
leaning on Romeo and Juliet.</i>

651
00:48:37,981 --> 00:48:42,611
<i>Mary, have you ever heard of a book
called Indian Love Lyrics?</i>

652
00:48:42,786 --> 00:48:45,152
- Yes.
- Well, I want to read it.

653
00:48:45,322 --> 00:48:48,883
Well, it's all yours.
It's over there in the poetry section.

654
00:48:51,662 --> 00:48:55,257
I beg your pardon, miss.
I wonder if you could help me find a book.

655
00:48:55,432 --> 00:48:59,528
<i>- What is it?
- The Decline And Fall of The Roman Empire.</i>

656
00:48:59,836 --> 00:49:02,669
Thanks, brother.
It's right over there in the History section.

657
00:49:02,839 --> 00:49:04,238
Thank you.

658
00:49:38,709 --> 00:49:41,542
<i>All the big professors state</i>

659
00:49:41,712 --> 00:49:45,307
<i>That everything should have a mate</i>

660
00:49:45,482 --> 00:49:48,883
<i>Birds and bees and flowers and trees</i>

661
00:49:49,052 --> 00:49:53,580
<i>All have romantic tendencies</i>

662
00:49:53,757 --> 00:49:56,988
<i>So far I have missed the he</i>

663
00:49:57,160 --> 00:50:01,221
<i>That fate decreed was meant for me</i>

664
00:50:01,398 --> 00:50:05,835
<i>I'm just living in a lull</i>

665
00:50:06,003 --> 00:50:12,499
<i>And I'll confess it's mighty dull</i>

666
00:50:13,844 --> 00:50:18,144
<i>Romeo had Juliet</i>

667
00:50:18,315 --> 00:50:22,911
<i>And Louis Xvl had Antoinette</i>

668
00:50:23,086 --> 00:50:27,750
<i>But I ain't got nobody</i>

669
00:50:27,924 --> 00:50:33,123
<i>And nobody's got me</i>

670
00:50:33,430 --> 00:50:37,992
<i>Pelleas had Melisande</i>

671
00:50:38,168 --> 00:50:42,730
<i>And Isabella had Ferdinand</i>

672
00:50:42,906 --> 00:50:47,240
<i>But I ain't got nobody</i>

673
00:50:47,411 --> 00:50:52,542
<i>And nobody's got me</i>

674
00:50:53,016 --> 00:50:57,715
<i>Welch Grape Juice has Irene Rich</i>

675
00:50:57,888 --> 00:51:02,120
<i>Minneapolis has Saint Paul</i>

676
00:51:02,292 --> 00:51:06,285
<i>Abercrombie has his Fitch</i>

677
00:51:06,463 --> 00:51:09,159
<i>But here I am crying
And sitting and sighing</i>

678
00:51:09,332 --> 00:51:12,495
<i>With no one at all</i>

679
00:51:12,669 --> 00:51:16,935
<i>Hans had Gretel by his side</i>

680
00:51:17,107 --> 00:51:21,737
<i>And Dr. Jekyll had Mr. Hyde</i>

681
00:51:21,912 --> 00:51:27,043
<i>But I ain't got nobody</i>

682
00:51:27,217 --> 00:51:33,713
<i>And nobody's got me</i>

683
00:51:40,764 --> 00:51:44,200
- Closing time?
- How did you guess?

684
00:51:49,940 --> 00:51:51,805
- Aren't they wonderful?
- Who?

685
00:51:51,975 --> 00:51:54,967
- Antony and Cleo...
- Yes, yes.

686
00:52:00,684 --> 00:52:05,678
Romeo! Wherefore art thou, Romeo?

687
00:52:05,856 --> 00:52:08,051
Scram, Juliet.

688
00:52:16,733 --> 00:52:20,533
<i>Lancelot had fair Elaine</i>

