I do forgive you, a thousandfold.

913
01:07:24,673 --> 01:07:28,803
My heart is bounding
like the surging sea.

914
01:07:28,978 --> 01:07:33,608
Wait. Would she think me impetuous
if I asked her for a tryst?

915
01:07:33,783 --> 01:07:35,307
I'll risk it.

916
01:07:35,484 --> 01:07:39,477
Miss Nelly, may I hope to see you again
on the morrow?

917
01:07:39,655 --> 01:07:43,614
Silly headstrong youth.
Shall we say the park?

918
01:07:43,793 --> 01:07:47,524
- At 3?
- Until 3, then, at the park.

919
01:07:48,397 --> 01:07:50,092
<i>Adieu. Adieu.</i>

920
01:07:50,266 --> 01:07:51,893
<i>- Adieu.
- Adieu.</i>

921
01:07:52,068 --> 01:07:56,471
<i>But heaven will protect</i>

922
01:07:56,639 --> 01:08:00,234
<i>The working girl</i>

923
01:08:00,409 --> 01:08:06,439
<i>The working girl</i>

924
01:08:16,659 --> 01:08:20,288
It has been three years
since Merriwether and I were made one.

925
01:08:20,463 --> 01:08:24,490
And fate has blessed us
with this lovely child.

926
01:08:24,967 --> 01:08:26,457
I thank you, kind fate...

927
01:08:26,635 --> 01:08:30,969
...for having guided my footsteps
from the gutters of ignominy.

928
01:08:31,140 --> 01:08:32,801
Oh, baby.

929
01:08:33,809 --> 01:08:37,643
- Nelly. My wife.
- My husband.

930
01:08:37,813 --> 01:08:40,509
Why do you hang your head in shame?

931
01:08:40,683 --> 01:08:45,586
Would that I could die here, I sullied
her pretty brow with such sordid news.

932
01:08:45,754 --> 01:08:49,485
Nelly, the mortgage is due,
and alas, I have no money.

933
01:08:49,658 --> 01:08:52,991
Oh, shame. Oh, agony.

934
01:08:53,496 --> 01:08:57,262
'Tis the squire, Nelly. Be brave.

935
01:08:58,567 --> 01:09:01,127
Well, my pretty doves, we meet again.

936
01:09:01,670 --> 01:09:03,604
'Tis the end.

937
01:09:04,373 --> 01:09:06,671
No, Merriwether. No. Not yet.

938
01:09:06,842 --> 01:09:10,642
Where there's life, there's hope.
Here, take this ring and pawn it.

939
01:09:10,813 --> 01:09:14,510
- No, Nelly, 'tis your wedding ring.
- This is no time for sentiment.

940
01:09:14,683 --> 01:09:15,911
Run, Merriwether.

941
01:09:16,085 --> 01:09:18,645
Now, Squire Poultice,
until this house belongs to you...

942
01:09:18,821 --> 01:09:21,187
...you are not welcome in it. Scram.

943
01:09:21,357 --> 01:09:24,986
Curse you, Nelly Newcombe.
But you have not heard the last of me.

944
01:09:25,161 --> 01:09:27,789
I'll get you yet.

945
01:09:46,315 --> 01:09:47,543
Here's your lemonade, sir.

946
01:09:47,716 --> 01:09:50,583
Nice of you to invite me for a refreshment
on such a hot day.

947
01:09:50,753 --> 01:09:53,722
- Little does he know.
- This lassie, awfully clever.

948
01:09:53,889 --> 01:09:56,585
With this, we'll work the trick.

949
01:10:22,685 --> 01:10:24,676
Good. Good.

950
01:10:24,853 --> 01:10:28,448
Come on, Squire Wire, old boy, let's you
and I have another little drink, huh?

951
01:10:28,624 --> 01:10:31,252
- Merriwether!
- It's my wife.

952
01:10:31,427 --> 01:10:34,794
<i>Father, dear Father
Come home with me now</i>

953
01:10:34,964 --> 01:10:38,593
<i>The clock in the steeple strikes</i>

954
01:10:39,702 --> 01:10:41,465
<i>One</i>

955
01:10:41,637 --> 01:10:45,573
<i>You said you were coming right home
With the dough</i>

956
01:10:45,741 --> 01:10:49,575
<i>As soon as Ma's ring you did pawn</i>

957
01:10:49,745 --> 01:10:53,738
<i>Come home, come home, come home.</i>

958
01:10:53,916 --> 01:10:55,247
My baby.

959
01:10:55,417 --> 01:10:59,820
<i>Please, Father, dear Father</i>

960
01:10:59,989 --> 01:11:00,978
My boy, Squire.

961
01:11:01,156 --> 01:11:04,819
<i>Come home</i>

962
01:11:04,994 --> 01:11:07,053
My little boy.

963
01:11:07,863 --> 01:11:10,423
My baby.

964
01:11:10,966 --> 01:11:13,025
So.

965
01:11:13,202 --> 01:11:15,295
You've been spying on me, huh?

966
01:11:15,471 --> 01:11:17,803
Merriwether,
you've been gone for two years.

967
01:11:17,973 --> 01:11:19,270
Where is the money?

968
01:11:19,441 --> 01:11:22,205
Money? What money
are you talking about, Nelly?

969
01:11:22,378 --> 01:11:25,347
The money for the mortgage.

970
01:11:26,282 --> 01:11:28,273
What happened to the money
for the mortgage?

971
01:11:28,450 --> 01:11:30,816
Your husband's bought rum
with the money, madame.

972
01:11:30,986 --> 01:11:32,578
Then all is lost.

973
01:11:32,755 --> 01:11:38,250
Now, I'll teach you
to meddle in my affairs.

974
01:11:39,295 --> 01:11:42,025
Benny, my child. Benny.
You brute. You brute.

975
01:11:42,197 --> 01:11:44,495
- No, Nelly, wait a minute.
- To strike the baby.

976
01:11:44,667 --> 01:11:48,763
- Where's he going?
- Benny, my child.

977
01:11:49,805 --> 01:11:51,830
You killed our baby.

978
01:11:52,007 --> 01:11:57,309
Unkind fate, this is too unfortunate.

979
01:11:58,080 --> 01:12:03,177
Look. Go on. Get out of here, Nelly.
Go on, Nelly! Get out of here.

980
01:12:05,020 --> 01:12:08,649
What have I done? My wife gone.

981
01:12:08,824 --> 01:12:12,282
My little baby gone. My home gone.

982
01:12:12,461 --> 01:12:14,827
Oh, shame, shame.

983
01:12:14,997 --> 01:12:18,091
How about a slug
of white lightning, partner?

984
01:12:18,267 --> 01:12:19,859
Well, I don't mind if I do, Miss...

985
01:12:20,035 --> 01:12:23,198
No. Take that vile stuff
out of my sight forever.

986
01:12:23,372 --> 01:12:25,966
I must redeem myself
in the light of heaven...

987
01:12:26,141 --> 01:12:29,770
...and save my Nelly
from a fate worse than death.

988
01:12:54,269 --> 01:12:57,727
You fiend incarnate.
You snake in the snow.

989
01:12:57,906 --> 01:13:01,603
Now, Miss Nelly,
I have come to help you.

990
01:13:01,777 --> 01:13:04,712
If you will marry me,
I can give you the niceties of life...

991
01:13:04,880 --> 01:13:08,475
...that you so richly deserve.

992
01:13:09,218 --> 01:13:12,153
Perhaps it would be better than suicide.

993
01:13:12,321 --> 01:13:15,620
- But I do not love you.
- My riches will make you love me.

994
01:13:15,791 --> 01:13:19,158
Now, just sit down here,
my pretty pigeon...

995
01:13:19,328 --> 01:13:22,786
...and sign this paper.

996
01:13:23,399 --> 01:13:28,393
- Sign.
- Hark. Methinks I hear dog barks.

997
01:13:29,938 --> 01:13:32,566
Hold those dogs.

998
01:13:34,643 --> 01:13:38,511
Just in the nick of time.
Stop, Nelly. Do not sign those papers.

999
01:13:38,680 --> 01:13:40,443
The old fox is up to his old tricks.

1000
01:13:40,616 --> 01:13:42,106
- My husband.
- My wife.

1001
01:13:42,284 --> 01:13:46,448
Curses. Curses.
Foiled again. But no. Not yet.

1002
01:13:46,622 --> 01:13:49,455
Quasimodo!

1003
01:13:50,826 --> 01:13:54,284
Tie them up and make sure
the pretty doves can't get away.

1004
01:13:54,463 --> 01:13:58,092
Mr. Goodpenny has an engagement
at the sawmill.

1005
01:13:58,867 --> 01:14:00,095
Mercy, Squire.

1006
01:14:00,269 --> 01:14:02,396
- Will you marry me?
- No. I'd rather die.

1007
01:14:02,571 --> 01:14:06,132
Then die you will, my pretty pet,
on the railroad tracks.

1008
01:14:06,308 --> 01:14:10,301
The railroad tracks? This is the end.

1009
01:14:23,292 --> 01:14:26,750
<i>Father, dear Father
Come home with me now</i>

1010
01:14:26,929 --> 01:14:30,160
<i>The clock in the steeple strikes</i>

1011
01:14:31,800 --> 01:14:33,768
<i>Two</i>

1012
01:14:33,936 --> 01:14:37,201
<i>Mother is tied to the railroad tracks</i>

1013
01:14:37,372 --> 01:14:40,933
<i>And the sawmill is going to get you</i>

1014
01:14:41,109 --> 01:14:45,136
Save me. Oh, save me. Save me.

1015
01:14:45,314 --> 01:14:47,578
My boy, you saved my life.
Where is your mother?

1016
01:14:47,749 --> 01:14:51,810
- Tied to the railroad tracks.
- Oh, then we must be off!

1017
01:14:54,523 --> 01:14:58,323
There they go. After them.

1018
01:15:10,506 --> 01:15:13,532
I gotta be going, Dad.
I got a date with a dream. So long.

1019
01:15:13,709 --> 01:15:15,768
So long, son.

1020
01:15:20,682 --> 01:15:24,413
Help. Help. Save me!

1021
01:15:24,586 --> 01:15:26,986
Help. Help me!

1022
01:15:31,693 --> 01:15:33,991
- I'll save you, my dear.
- Save me.

1023
01:15:34,162 --> 01:15:36,187
Here comes the train.

1024
01:15:51,780 --> 01:15:56,046
- My hero.
- Love triumphs over all.

1025
01:16:16,838 --> 01:16:18,669
Hey, let me down.

1026
01:16:18,840 --> 01:16:21,775
- Hey, we forgot Willie.
- Let me down.

1027
01:16:22,611 --> 01:16:24,203
It's Willie up there!
Pull him down.

1028
01:16:25,247 --> 01:16:26,612
Weren't they splendid?

1029
01:16:26,782 --> 01:16:29,410
Wonderful.
I don't know how they've done it.

1030
01:16:29,585 --> 01:16:31,382
Come and help me with the refreshments.

1031
01:16:31,553 --> 01:16:33,646
Why, I wouldn't miss it for the world.

1032
01:16:33,822 --> 01:16:37,519
- Hurry up, will you, Phil?
- I'm hurrying. Hold still.

1033
01:16:37,693 --> 01:16:39,524
Hold still.

1034
01:16:39,695 --> 01:16:41,026
What's the matter?

1035
01:16:41,196 --> 01:16:43,858
I socked my arm
when they pulled me up the last time.

1036
01:16:44,032 --> 01:16:47,524
They yanked the line too hard and I felt like
I was going through with wall.

1037
01:16:47,703 --> 01:16:51,298
- Here, let me take a look at it.
- No. No. Leave it alone. It's okay.

1038
01:16:51,473 --> 01:16:54,442
- Just a little sore, that's all.
- You were great, Mary.

1039
01:16:54,610 --> 01:16:56,601
- Thanks. You were swell too, Jimmy.
- Thanks.

1040
01:16:56,778 --> 01:16:58,245
You're coming over to the house?

1041
01:16:58,413 --> 01:17:00,973
- I'd like to. That is, if you're not too tired?
- Oh, no.

1042
01:17:01,149 --> 01:17:03,743
- You've got to take good care of yourself.
- I will.

1043
01:17:03,919 --> 01:17:06,217
Hey, Jimmy.
Have you seen Mr. Mollison yet?

1044
01:17:06,388 --> 01:17:09,585
No. But don't worry about it.
I won't leave until I get the $ 150.

1045
01:17:09,758 --> 01:17:13,091
Thattaboy.
Oh, great, Barbara Frances. Terrific.

1046
01:17:13,261 --> 01:17:18,062
- Yeah, you were very good, Barbara.
- Thank you. You're so very kind.

1047
01:17:18,934 --> 01:17:21,266
I have my car, Jimmy.
Could I drive you home?

1048
01:17:21,436 --> 01:17:23,301
We were all going over to Mary's and...

1049
01:17:23,472 --> 01:17:26,600
- Well, fine. Then I'll drop you off.
- But you don't have to...

1050
01:17:26,775 --> 01:17:29,073
- Hey, Jimmy. Jimmy Connors.
- Why, here I am, sir.

1051
01:17:29,244 --> 01:17:31,940
Here's your check for $ 150.
And you certainly deserve it.

1052
01:17:32,114 --> 01:17:34,275
This was the finest show
we've had in Riverwood.

1053
01:17:34,449 --> 01:17:38,180
Thanks, Mr. Mollison. We appreciate it.
Looks like we're on our way to Chicago.

1054
01:17:38,353 --> 01:17:40,480
- You bet we are.
- Lf we can dig up $50 more.

1055
01:17:40,656 --> 01:17:41,884
Here we come!

1056
01:17:48,530 --> 01:17:50,862
Well, goodnight.
I'm sorry you can't come in.

1057
01:17:51,033 --> 01:17:53,558
We won't be late.
We're only having a few refreshments.

1058
01:17:53,735 --> 01:17:56,932
Thank you, but I'm expecting
my mother and father back from New York.

1059
01:17:57,105 --> 01:17:59,005
- I really must run.
- I'm sorry. Goodnight.

1060
01:17:59,174 --> 01:18:01,506
- Goodnight.
- Goodnight, Barbara.

1061
01:18:01,677 --> 01:18:05,044
Jimmy, could I see you a minute?

1062
01:18:08,583 --> 01:18:11,245
Dad's giving me a party
at the country club next Saturday.

1063
01:18:11,420 --> 01:18:13,012
Will you come?

1064
01:18:13,689 --> 01:18:17,489
Why, I'd love to.
That's if I'm gonna be in town.

1065
01:18:17,659 --> 01:18:19,251
Oh, I'm so glad.

1066
01:18:19,428 --> 01:18:23,797
The only trouble is, I haven't been able
to make up my mind about the music.

1067
01:18:23,965 --> 01:18:25,990
- You mean, you haven't hired a band yet?
- No.

1068
01:18:26,168 --> 01:18:28,966
- But I must decide before I see my father.
- Sure, you do.

1069
01:18:29,137 --> 01:18:31,537
Well, maybe I could help you decide.

1070
01:18:31,707 --> 01:18:35,040
You might drive home with me
and talk to Dad. He'll be there.

1071
01:18:35,210 --> 01:18:38,509
- I hate to spoil your evening, but...
- oh, no, no. Not at all.

1072
01:18:38,680 --> 01:18:41,478
See you later. I've got
some important business to attend to.

1073
01:18:41,650 --> 01:18:44,551
Hey, Willie, take care of Mary, will you?
Slide over.

1074
01:18:46,188 --> 01:18:47,416
But, Jimmy.

1075
01:18:47,589 --> 01:18:50,581
Some birds just gotta be shot twice
before they stop flying.

1076
01:18:53,662 --> 01:18:57,223
I knew that blonde was a Jonah
the moment I saw her.

1077
01:19:00,435 --> 01:19:03,529
Would you and Annie go on inside?
I got something to say to Mary.

1078
01:19:03,705 --> 01:19:07,869
- What's the big secret?
- Come on, Squire, let's have a demitasse.

1079
01:19:12,881 --> 01:19:14,576
Mary?

1080
01:19:15,851 --> 01:19:17,148
What is it, Willie?

1081
01:19:17,319 --> 01:19:20,345
There's something I've wanted to ask you
for an awful long time.

1082
01:19:20,522 --> 01:19:22,456
Yes?

1083
01:19:22,624 --> 01:19:26,116
Whenever I had the opportunity,
I never had the courage.

1084
01:19:26,294 --> 01:19:29,923
Whenever I had the courage,
I never had the opportunity.

1085
01:19:30,098 --> 01:19:31,861
Now I got both.

1086
01:19:32,434 --> 01:19:34,800
Willie, what is it?

1087
01:19:37,506 --> 01:19:38,939
Will you marry me?

1088
01:19:41,309 --> 01:19:44,676
I don't expect you
to give me an answer right away.

1089
01:19:44,846 --> 01:19:48,873
- Well, but, Willie...
- It isn't as if I just met you.

1090
01:19:49,050 --> 01:19:52,110
I remember the first day I saw you.

1091
01:19:52,287 --> 01:19:54,949
You were wearing gym bloomers.

1092
01:19:55,123 --> 01:19:58,388
I was just getting out of Julius Caesar
and you were laughing.

1093
01:19:58,560 --> 01:20:00,027
Oh, Willie, you're the cutest...

1094
01:20:00,195 --> 01:20:03,562
I know I'm not
the best-looking guy in town...

1095
01:20:03,732 --> 01:20:06,257
...but I'll always love you
and I'll be true to you...

1096
01:20:06,434 --> 01:20:08,868
...and I won't go out with other girls.

1097
01:20:09,037 --> 01:20:10,971
Oh, Willie.

1098
01:20:11,139 --> 01:20:15,576
That's the nicest thing
anyone's ever said to me in my whole life.

1099
01:20:15,744 --> 01:20:18,178
And I'm very grateful.

1100
01:20:21,082 --> 01:20:24,142
But I'm much too young
to think of getting married.

1101
01:20:26,688 --> 01:20:29,282
Of course I'm not in any particular hurry.

1102
01:20:32,594 --> 01:20:36,325
- Willie, how old are you?
- Thirteen going on 14.

1103
01:20:36,498 --> 01:20:38,489
- Willie.
- Yes, ma'am?

1104
01:20:38,667 --> 01:20:43,104
Your mother phoned and wants you home.
She says it's time for you to go to bed.

1105
01:20:49,678 --> 01:20:51,703
Goodnight, Willie.

1106
01:20:53,181 --> 01:20:54,808
Goodnight.

1107
01:21:02,490 --> 01:21:05,857
- This is my favorite room in the house.
- It is?

1108
01:21:06,027 --> 01:21:08,222
Someday, I'm gonna have
an enormous yacht.

1109
01:21:08,396 --> 01:21:12,662
- Wouldn't you love to go to the South Seas?
- Yeah, it might be nice in the wintertime.

1110
01:21:12,834 --> 01:21:16,167
There aren't very many good-looking boys
in this town, are there?

1111
01:21:17,339 --> 01:21:19,432
Here, Jimmy, drink this.

1112
01:21:21,743 --> 01:21:23,802
- All right now?
- Yeah.

1113
01:21:23,979 --> 01:21:26,345
Just got my pipes tangled up.

1114
01:21:26,514 --> 01:21:29,108
You know, Jimmy,
when I look back and remember...

1115
01:21:29,284 --> 01:21:33,516
<i>...the thousands of dates I've had
with so many different boys...</i>

1116
01:21:33,688 --> 01:21:37,283
<i>When I think of the time I've wasted,
the empty hours...</i>

1117
01:21:37,459 --> 01:21:41,589
- I wouldn't say that.
- James.

1118
01:21:41,763 --> 01:21:43,526
Do you really want to kiss me?

1119
01:21:47,002 --> 01:21:49,300
- Barbara?
- Who's that?

1120
01:21:49,471 --> 01:21:51,769
It's Mother and Dad. They're back.

1121
01:21:51,940 --> 01:21:53,373
- Hello, darling.
- Hello, Mother.

1122
01:21:53,541 --> 01:21:55,338
- My dear.
- Hello, Dad.

1123
01:21:55,510 --> 01:21:58,946
Hello. Well, what's this?
Another young man?

1124
01:21:59,114 --> 01:22:01,207
I want you to meet
a very talented musician...

1125
01:22:01,383 --> 01:22:03,544
...and one of my dearest friends,
James Connors.

1126
01:22:03,718 --> 01:22:05,015
- How are you?
- How do you do?

1127
01:22:05,186 --> 01:22:06,483
- How do you do?
- Mrs. Morgan.

1128
01:22:06,655 --> 01:22:07,986
What do you play, young man?

1129
01:22:08,156 --> 01:22:10,590
I kind of mess around
with the drums a little bit.

1130
01:22:10,759 --> 01:22:13,421
James has the most wonderful orchestra
in the whole world.

1131
01:22:13,595 --> 01:22:16,530
And he's volunteered to play
for my birthday party for only $50.

1132
01:22:16,698 --> 01:22:20,190
- Isn't that wonderful?
- Well, that's very nice of you, Mr. Connors.

1133
01:22:20,368 --> 01:22:22,700
But, Barbara,
I wish I'd known about this before.

1134
01:22:22,904 --> 01:22:25,873
- Why, Dad?
- I'm afraid I've made other arrangements.

1135
01:22:26,041 --> 01:22:28,032
But, Dad, I promised James.

1136
01:22:28,209 --> 01:22:31,042
We play fine music, Mr. Morgan.
We do an awfully good job.

1137
01:22:31,212 --> 01:22:35,148
Well, I'm sure of that, son.
But I've already signed the contract.

1138
01:22:35,317 --> 01:22:37,615
- Oh, I see.
- But we want you to come to the party.

1139
01:22:37,786 --> 01:22:41,153
Especially if you're a musician,
then you can bring your whole orchestra.

1140
01:22:41,323 --> 01:22:44,918
That's kind of you. I don't know whether
we can make it or not, but we'll try.

1141
01:22:45,093 --> 01:22:47,994
- I hope so.
- How about a Coke, young man?

1142
01:22:48,163 --> 01:22:51,655
- Thanks.
- We'll get to your band. Market's going up.

1143
01:22:51,833 --> 01:22:53,630
- Going to have a lot of parties.
- Sure.

1144
01:22:53,802 --> 01:22:57,863
Now, don't you worry about it.
And we wanna have you try and be there.

1145
01:22:58,373 --> 01:23:01,706
It isn't every day you get a chance
to hear Paul Whiteman.

1146
01:23:02,544 --> 01:23:04,136
- Paul Whiteman?
- Yes.

1147
01:23:04,312 --> 01:23:07,804
- He'll be winding up his tour near here and...
- Paul Whiteman, here?

1148
01:23:07,983 --> 01:23:12,079
Yes. We had a hard job getting him
but I have a lot of good friends.

1149
01:23:12,253 --> 01:23:16,212
Paul Whiteman in Riverwood?
Oh, thanks. Thanks. We'll be there.

1150
01:23:16,391 --> 01:23:17,756
Just try and keep us away.

1151
01:23:17,926 --> 01:23:20,520
Paul Whiteman. Paul Whiteman.
Well, goodbye, every...

1152
01:23:20,695 --> 01:23:22,890
Pardon me.
Glad to have met you, Mrs. Morgan.

1153
01:23:23,064 --> 01:23:27,262
You too, Mr. Morgan. I mean, Mrs. Morgan.
You know what I mean anyway.

1154
01:23:27,435 --> 01:23:33,203
Sorry. Thank you. Thanks a lot.
Goodbye. And we'll be there too. Yes, sir.

1155
01:25:02,363 --> 01:25:04,490
In behalf of Mrs. Morgan and myself...

1156
01:25:04,666 --> 01:25:10,161
...I want to welcome all of Barbara Frances'
friends to her 18th birthday party.

1157
01:25:10,338 --> 01:25:12,602
We also want to welcome
Mr. Whiteman and his band.

1158
01:25:12,774 --> 01:25:16,437
And tell them
we are glad to have them with us.

1159
01:25:20,048 --> 01:25:22,846
Thank you, Mr. Morgan,
and we're mighty glad to be here too.

1160
01:25:23,017 --> 01:25:26,214
And now, I want you to have
the very best of good times.

1161
01:25:26,387 --> 01:25:29,550
Paul, it's all yours.

1162
01:25:40,335 --> 01:25:44,135
- Say, your old man's all right.
- What did you expect him to be?

1163
01:25:48,776 --> 01:25:52,234
- How about this dance, Mary?
- Thanks, but I'm wondering about Willie.

1164
01:25:52,413 --> 01:25:54,813
- You haven't seen him dancing, have you?
- I haven't.

1165
01:25:54,983 --> 01:25:57,508
Last time I saw him
he was hanging around on the porch.

1166
01:25:57,685 --> 01:26:01,052
Well, thanks. I think I'd better go find him.
He's kind of shy, you know.

1167
01:26:01,222 --> 01:26:03,247
We want him to have
a good time, don't we?

1168
01:26:03,424 --> 01:26:05,483
Oh, sure we do.

1169
01:26:12,734 --> 01:26:16,033
They certainly are swell.
But we've got just as good a brass section.

1170
01:26:16,204 --> 01:26:17,466
Just as loud anyhow.

1171
01:26:17,639 --> 01:26:21,075
Yeah, only they push the valves down
at the same time.

1172
01:26:23,912 --> 01:26:26,676
Hello, Willie. What are you doing
out here?

1173
01:26:26,848 --> 01:26:30,443
- Nothing.
- Well, come on inside and let's dance.

1174
01:26:30,618 --> 01:26:32,085
No, thanks.

1175
01:26:32,253 --> 01:26:35,086
You've acted awfully funny
ever since the night of the show.

1176
01:26:35,256 --> 01:26:37,224
Is there anything wrong?

1177
01:26:38,259 --> 01:26:40,727
I got things on my mind.

1178
01:26:41,763 --> 01:26:44,129
Well, I won't bother you then.

1179
01:26:48,102 --> 01:26:52,163
Willie, you're not mad at anything,
are you?

1180
01:26:52,340 --> 01:26:55,173
- No, I'm not mad.
- That's swell.

1181
01:26:55,343 --> 01:26:59,746
- Willie, what's wrong?
- Just my arm. It hurts something awful.

1182
01:26:59,914 --> 01:27:03,247
- Your arm?
- Don't, please. Don't touch it.

1183
01:27:03,418 --> 01:27:05,909
Willie, maybe you should go home.

1184
01:27:06,087 --> 01:27:08,487
I don't wanna miss all the fun.

1185
01:27:08,656 --> 01:27:10,749
Have you seen a doctor?

1186
01:27:10,925 --> 01:27:14,122
- They don't know nothing.
- Willie, that's very foolish.

1187
01:27:14,295 --> 01:27:16,957
If there's something wrong,
you should have it looked at.

1188
01:27:17,131 --> 01:27:20,191
Promise me you'll go see a doctor
tomorrow morning.

1189
01:27:22,403 --> 01:27:25,930
Okay, I'll go, but it won't do any good.

1190
01:27:26,107 --> 01:27:28,598
But nevertheless, you promised.

1191
01:27:29,611 --> 01:27:31,238
Yeah.

1192
01:27:31,412 --> 01:27:35,007
Well, let's go on inside and watch, huh?

1193
01:27:35,183 --> 01:27:36,707
Come on.

1194
01:27:50,732 --> 01:27:52,723
Hey, kids. I just met Paul Whiteman.

1195
01:27:52,900 --> 01:27:54,299
- You did?
- Swell, Phil.

1196
01:27:54,469 --> 01:27:57,836
Hey, Jimmy, take a load of that tenor sax.
No wonder he can make it moan.

1197
01:27:58,006 --> 01:28:00,133
He didn't win that clarinet
at a raffle either.

1198
01:28:00,308 --> 01:28:03,607
Gosh, I'd sure like to take a feel
of those sticks.

1199
01:28:03,778 --> 01:28:06,440
- It wouldn't hurt anybody, would it?
- No, go ahead, Jimmy.

1200
01:28:06,614 --> 01:28:09,447
Go ahead. Sure. Go on.

1201
01:28:09,617 --> 01:28:12,916
- Oh, gee, do you think he should?
- Sure, why not? It can't do any harm.

1202
01:28:13,087 --> 01:28:14,918
Oh, I don't know.

1203
01:28:17,025 --> 01:28:21,052
- Hey, Leonard, what a set of skins.
- Yeah.

1204
01:28:22,830 --> 01:28:26,493
Gosh, with a set of drums like these,
a guy could get in the White House.

1205
01:28:27,535 --> 01:28:31,266
Boy, if I owned this,
I'd just sit around all day and look at it.

1206
01:28:31,439 --> 01:28:33,066
Beauty.

1207
01:28:33,241 --> 01:28:36,677
Just as easy.

1208
01:28:39,047 --> 01:28:41,948
- Look, Jimmy. Isn't this a honey?
- Gosh, it sure is.

1209
01:28:42,116 --> 01:28:45,244
- Gee, I never felt more in the mood.
- Me neither.

1210
01:28:45,420 --> 01:28:48,355
Say, it wouldn't do any harm
to knock out a couple, would it?

1211
01:28:48,523 --> 01:28:49,751
- No.
- No, it wouldn't.

1212
01:28:49,924 --> 01:28:51,983
- What are we waiting for?
- Just a downbeat.

1213
01:28:52,160 --> 01:28:55,254
Well, all right then, let's get ready.
Sid, get over at the piano.

1214
01:28:55,430 --> 01:28:57,398
One, two.

1215
01:29:49,217 --> 01:29:51,651
<i>There's a boy down on our street</i>

1216
01:29:51,819 --> 01:29:53,753
<i>Plays the drums with such a beat</i>

1217
01:29:53,921 --> 01:29:58,324
<i>You cannot control your feet
When you hear the drummer boy</i>

1218
01:29:58,493 --> 01:30:02,759
<i>In the morning when you wake
You can hear him take a break</i>

1219
01:30:02,930 --> 01:30:07,526
<i>Soon the whole street starts to shake
When they hear the drummer boy</i>

1220
01:30:07,735 --> 01:30:12,365
<i>Bing bang, ding dang
He's so nimble on the cymbal</i>

1221
01:30:12,540 --> 01:30:16,977
<i>Bing bong, ding dong
When he plays 'em he just slays 'em</i>

1222
01:30:17,145 --> 01:30:21,514
<i>All your troubles fly away
Every day's a happy day</i>

1223
01:30:21,682 --> 01:30:23,616
<i>Everything will be okay</i>

1224
01:30:23,785 --> 01:30:28,188
<i>When you hear the drummer boy play</i>

1225
01:30:45,973 --> 01:30:48,441
Say, it looks like somebody's
kind of taken over here.

1226
01:30:48,609 --> 01:30:51,772
- Yeah, and not bad either, Pop.
- You're telling me.

1227
01:30:51,946 --> 01:30:53,811
<i>Gather 'round, all you chums</i>

1228
01:30:56,451 --> 01:30:58,578
<i>Watch this cat spin those drums</i>

1229
01:31:01,088 --> 01:31:02,988
<i>Swing it, brother, beat that hide</i>

1230
01:31:05,760 --> 01:31:08,524
<i>Take us on a jivin' ride</i>

1231
01:31:10,097 --> 01:31:14,625
<i>This is what the doc prescribes
For a case of jibs and jibes</i>

1232
01:31:14,802 --> 01:31:18,898
<i>Drummer boy please give out
On those vibes</i>

1233
01:32:39,654 --> 01:32:45,854
<i>Hear that drummer boy play</i>

1234
01:32:57,038 --> 01:32:58,437
Goldie, you boys go on ahead.

1235
01:32:58,606 --> 01:33:00,972
- I'll meet you at the hotel.
- Right, Pop.

1236
01:33:01,142 --> 01:33:02,700
Come in.

1237
01:33:03,945 --> 01:33:05,412
You wanted to see me?

1238
01:33:05,580 --> 01:33:07,605
Sure. Come on in.

1239
01:33:10,117 --> 01:33:11,448
My name's Connors.

1240
01:33:11,619 --> 01:33:14,087
- I know. Mine's Whiteman.
- Yeah.

1241
01:33:14,255 --> 01:33:16,553
- Won't you sit down?
- Thank you.

1242
01:33:16,724 --> 01:33:20,353
I guess I ought to apologize for barging
up there and taking over like I did...

1243
01:33:20,528 --> 01:33:23,622
...but we wanted to give you
an audition for your contest.

1244
01:33:23,798 --> 01:33:27,097
It was a good audition.
How long you been playing the drums?

1245
01:33:27,268 --> 01:33:28,667
Ever since I was a kid.

1246
01:33:28,836 --> 01:33:31,361
- You're through school?
- Yes, sir. I've just graduated.

1247
01:33:31,539 --> 01:33:35,771
- Well, I bet you're mighty happy about that.
- Well, I made it, but I had to slide.

1248
01:33:35,943 --> 01:33:37,308
What are you going to do next?

1249
01:33:37,478 --> 01:33:40,936
Keep on pounding the drums
as long as anybody will listen to me.

1250
01:33:41,115 --> 01:33:44,084
Jimmy,
you're a mighty talented young fellow.

1251
01:33:44,251 --> 01:33:46,276
And I think I ought
to do something about it.

1252
01:33:46,454 --> 01:33:49,582
One of my boys, a swell saxophone player
and a mighty fine fellow...

1253
01:33:49,757 --> 01:33:51,622
...is starting his own band in New York.

1254
01:33:51,792 --> 01:33:54,420
They open Thursday.
The drum spot's open.

1255
01:33:54,595 --> 01:33:56,187
How'd you like to have that job?

1256
01:34:01,102 --> 01:34:02,364
Oh, you're kidding me.

1257
01:34:02,536 --> 01:34:05,835
They open Thursday.
You'll have to be there if you want the job.

1258
01:34:07,642 --> 01:34:09,337
I want the...

1259
01:34:11,846 --> 01:34:13,609
New York.

1260
01:34:15,082 --> 01:34:16,310
Yeah.

1261
01:34:16,484 --> 01:34:19,009
Yeah, why, I could go home
and pack right now.

1262
01:34:19,186 --> 01:34:21,051
Wait a minute, Jimmy. Don't get excited.

1263
01:34:21,222 --> 01:34:23,452
I'm not excited.
Who's excited, Mr. Whiteman?

1264
01:34:23,624 --> 01:34:26,787
Think it over and let me know
in the morning. I'm at the Wentworth.

1265
01:34:26,961 --> 01:34:29,930
The Wentworth?
Well, I don't have to think it over.

1266
01:34:30,097 --> 01:34:31,724
I could just have to tell my mom.

1267
01:34:31,899 --> 01:34:35,232
Well, I could phone you the first thing
in the morning. Say, about 7:30?

1268
01:34:35,403 --> 01:34:37,803
That's okay but I think
10 would be a little better.

1269
01:34:37,972 --> 01:34:41,999
Ten o'clock. Oh, gosh.
Thanks a lot, Mr. Whiteman. Gee.

1270
01:34:42,176 --> 01:34:44,576
- You're on the level?
- Sure I'm on the level, Jimmy.

1271
01:34:44,745 --> 01:34:48,203
Oh, gosh. Well, thanks.
I'll phone you the first thing in the morning.

1272
01:34:48,382 --> 01:34:49,974
Good night.

1273
01:34:53,554 --> 01:34:56,682
Hey, Mom. Mom!

1274
01:34:56,857 --> 01:34:59,291
Mom. Mom, you awake?

1275
01:34:59,460 --> 01:35:02,258
- Jimmy, what on earth...?
- It's happened. I told you it would.

1276
01:35:02,430 --> 01:35:03,954
We're on our way. I've got a job.

1277
01:35:04,131 --> 01:35:06,929
- Job? What do you mean?
- Mr. Whiteman heard our band tonight.

1278
01:35:07,101 --> 01:35:10,161
Paul Whiteman. He's offered me
a job with an orchestra in New York.

1279
01:35:10,337 --> 01:35:11,668
All of our troubles are over.

1280
01:35:11,839 --> 01:35:15,002
Jimmy, I'm so glad for you, son,
and I'm so proud.

1281
01:35:15,176 --> 01:35:17,644
Oh, gosh, Mom, just think of it.
New York.

1282
01:35:17,812 --> 01:35:20,303
Oh, that's right.

1283
01:35:20,481 --> 01:35:24,144
You said you'd be going
to New York right away.

1284
01:35:24,318 --> 01:35:25,717
Yeah.

1285
01:35:26,454 --> 01:35:28,649
Have you told Mary and Phillip?

1286
01:35:28,823 --> 01:35:31,417
Well, I thought I'd wait
until I got the whole thing set.

1287
01:35:31,592 --> 01:35:35,221
- I've got to see Mr. Whiteman tomorrow.
- I wonder what they'll say.

1288
01:35:35,830 --> 01:35:37,388
<i>Why, they'll...</i>

1289
01:35:37,565 --> 01:35:39,328
- Why?
- And the band.

1290
01:35:39,500 --> 01:35:42,264
Everybody's looking forward so
to going to Chicago.

1291
01:35:42,436 --> 01:35:44,927
Everybody's been working so hard.

1292
01:35:45,106 --> 01:35:48,166
Working for the whole group.

1293
01:35:48,342 --> 01:35:50,867
- I know what you're thinking but...
- Do you?

1294
01:35:51,045 --> 01:35:52,876
I remember when you started the band.

1295
01:35:53,047 --> 01:35:57,780
When you told me that they believed in you,
had faith in you to stick by you.

1296
01:35:57,952 --> 01:36:00,147
And what suddenly happens
to them now?

1297
01:36:00,554 --> 01:36:02,749
They're the same people.

1298
01:36:03,524 --> 01:36:08,962
But this is my one big chance.
I can't give it up. Don't ask me to.

1299
01:36:09,130 --> 01:36:12,293
You'd be climbing
the first rung of the ladder.

1300
01:36:12,466 --> 01:36:15,333
By walking out on your friends.

1301
01:36:23,244 --> 01:36:24,836
<i>Yeah, I...</i>

1302
01:36:25,713 --> 01:36:27,510
I know it now.

1303
01:36:28,349 --> 01:36:30,943
I guess I just didn't stop to think.

1304
01:36:32,286 --> 01:36:34,254
I thought it'd be wonderful
for both of us.

1305
01:36:34,421 --> 01:36:36,889
And so it can be, Jimmy.

1306
01:36:37,191 --> 01:36:40,024
But not quite so fast.

1307
01:36:48,102 --> 01:36:49,501
Where are you going, son?

1308
01:36:51,739 --> 01:36:53,604
You know where I'm going.

1309
01:36:58,646 --> 01:37:02,309
So I'm afraid I won't be able
to accept the job, Mr. Whiteman.

1310
01:37:02,483 --> 01:37:05,816
<i>I thought I could, but I just got
through talking to my mother and...</i>

1311
01:37:05,986 --> 01:37:08,716
Well, she straightened me out
on a few things.

1312
01:37:08,889 --> 01:37:11,756
Mothers have a knack at that sort of thing,
don't they, Jimmy?

1313
01:37:11,926 --> 01:37:14,690
Yes, sir. You know, ever since
you made that announcement...

1314
01:37:14,862 --> 01:37:17,524
<i>...about a guest appearance
on your broadcast...</i>

1315
01:37:17,698 --> 01:37:19,893
Why, that's been our ambition.

1316
01:37:20,868 --> 01:37:22,096
We played dates.

1317
01:37:22,269 --> 01:37:25,636
We even gave a show to try to raise
enough money to get to Chicago...

1318
01:37:25,806 --> 01:37:27,865
...to give an audition.

1319
01:37:28,042 --> 01:37:30,670
But that's before we knew
you were coming here.

1320
01:37:30,845 --> 01:37:32,540
Jimmy, did you form that band?

1321
01:37:32,980 --> 01:37:34,379
Yes, sir.

1322
01:37:35,916 --> 01:37:37,941
I kind of cooked it up.

1323
01:37:39,820 --> 01:37:42,050
But I can't very well
pull out on them now.

1324
01:37:44,491 --> 01:37:47,756
That's good enough for me.
Jimmy, let me tell you something.

1325
01:37:47,928 --> 01:37:50,954
When I started out, a band was
a bunch of boys with instruments...

1326
01:37:51,131 --> 01:37:54,726
...who got together and beat out rhythm
for the rest of the folks to dance to.

1327
01:37:54,902 --> 01:37:57,496
But now it's a profession,
and a mighty important one.

1328
01:37:57,671 --> 01:38:01,368
Take the big bandleader of today.
He's almost a household word.

1329
01:38:01,542 --> 01:38:05,273
He's as well known as your
biggest picture actor or baseball player.

1330
01:38:05,446 --> 01:38:09,644
Fred Waring, Kay Kyser, Glenn Miller.
All very popular.

1331
01:38:09,817 --> 01:38:12,980
But once they were a little guy
called Jimmy Connors who...

1332
01:38:13,153 --> 01:38:14,711
...just sort of cooked things up.

1333
01:38:17,091 --> 01:38:19,582
But with this popularity
comes a great responsibility.

1334
01:38:20,227 --> 01:38:23,993
Rhythm can either excite the worst in us
or bring out the best.

1335
01:38:24,164 --> 01:38:25,995
Take that little fellow on the street.

1336
01:38:26,166 --> 01:38:28,896
Teach him to blow a horn
and he'll never blow a safe.

1337
01:38:29,069 --> 01:38:32,004
You know, rhythm is really
a wonderful thing.

1338
01:38:32,172 --> 01:38:34,800
Sometimes I think
rhythm almost runs the world.

1339
01:38:34,975 --> 01:38:39,275
In a little baby, the first thing that starts
is his rhythm. His little heart starts to beat.

1340
01:38:39,446 --> 01:38:42,006
And every different city
has a different kind of rhythm.

1341
01:38:42,182 --> 01:38:44,514
In your car,
if the engine's missing and jerking...

1342
01:38:44,685 --> 01:38:48,086
...or you feel the bump of a flat tire,
rhythm tells something's wrong.

1343
01:38:48,255 --> 01:38:51,520
And if you call a doctor,
the first thing he does is check your rhythm.

1344
01:38:51,692 --> 01:38:55,719
He feels your pulse to find if your rhythm
is solid and your beat's strong.

1345
01:38:55,896 --> 01:38:59,059
So, Jimmy, when we get
to the last eight bars of the big tune...

1346
01:38:59,233 --> 01:39:02,168
...and the old ticker
kind of slows down...

1347
01:39:02,336 --> 01:39:06,966
...no matter what's wrong with us,
the last thing to stop is our rhythm.

1348
01:39:11,946 --> 01:39:14,540
After listening to a lot of bands
all over the country...

1349
01:39:14,715 --> 01:39:18,879
...I don't think it would be fair to select one
and give them the guest spot on that show.

1350
01:39:19,053 --> 01:39:21,578
No, there's too many good ones.

1351
01:39:22,156 --> 01:39:23,623
I've put up a $500 prize...

1352
01:39:23,791 --> 01:39:27,750
...and I'm gonna devote my whole
program for a high school band contest.

1353
01:39:27,928 --> 01:39:29,122
I'm going to play it safe.

1354
01:39:29,296 --> 01:39:31,457
I'm gonna let the public
worry about who's best.

1355
01:39:31,632 --> 01:39:33,691
Gosh, that sounds terrific, Mr. Whiteman.

1356
01:39:33,867 --> 01:39:37,963
I've already selected three bands,
but I think I'll make it four.

1357
01:39:38,138 --> 01:39:39,935
Do you want to try?

1358
01:39:41,842 --> 01:39:44,367
- Do we?
- Chicago, Saturday night.

1359
01:39:44,545 --> 01:39:48,140
- Will you be there?
- Why, you couldn't keep us away.

1360
01:39:52,252 --> 01:39:55,312
<i>- Well, what's the matter, Jimmy?
- Oh, I...</i>

1361
01:39:55,689 --> 01:39:57,589
I forgot, Mr. Whiteman.

1362
01:39:57,758 --> 01:40:01,250
It's gonna cost us $200
to get the band to Chicago.

1363
01:40:01,428 --> 01:40:05,831
I've figured it out.
We've only got 150.

1364
01:40:08,035 --> 01:40:13,632
Mr. Whiteman, do you think you could see
your way clear to give me a loan of $50?

1365
01:40:13,807 --> 01:40:15,638
I'll give you my personal note.

1366
01:40:15,809 --> 01:40:18,141
Well, what have you got
for collateral, Jimmy?

1367
01:40:18,312 --> 01:40:21,679
Well, I could put up my drums.

1368
01:40:21,849 --> 01:40:24,181
They mean more to me
than anything in the world.

1369
01:40:24,551 --> 01:40:26,610
You'd really do that, Jimmy?

1370
01:40:26,787 --> 01:40:28,186
Yes, I would, Mr. Whiteman.

1371
01:40:28,355 --> 01:40:31,290
- It's a deal. There you are.
- Oh, gosh.

1372
01:40:31,458 --> 01:40:34,427
Thanks. You won't have to wait long,
not if there's a $500 prize.

1373
01:40:34,595 --> 01:40:37,530
I wouldn't be too confident.
You might get a little competition.

1374
01:40:37,698 --> 01:40:40,599
We're not afraid
of a bunch of kids from high school.

1375
01:40:41,902 --> 01:40:43,870
- Hurry up, you're late.
- Is everybody here?

1376
01:40:44,038 --> 01:40:46,165
- Music hasn't been passed out.
- Where's Willie?

1377
01:40:46,340 --> 01:40:48,137
- He isn't here.
- I'll scalp that midget.

1378
01:40:48,308 --> 01:40:49,775
- Run over the old ones.
- Jimmy!

1379
01:40:49,943 --> 01:40:53,572
Mrs. Brewster phoned, Willie's terribly sick.
The doctor's there. She wants us.

1380
01:40:53,747 --> 01:40:55,044
What? Let's get going.

1381
01:40:57,251 --> 01:41:01,688
I'm so glad you've come.
I'll call the doctor.

1382
01:41:02,456 --> 01:41:04,117
Oh, I'm afraid it's awfully serious.

1383
01:41:04,291 --> 01:41:08,057
- I hope not. What's the matter, doctor?
- From what I gather, he injured his arm...

1384
01:41:08,228 --> 01:41:10,696
...when he was swung up
on that wire during your show.

1385
01:41:10,864 --> 01:41:12,889
- His arm.
- It's perfectly possible for him...

1386
01:41:13,067 --> 01:41:16,400
...to have gone around all this time
without knowing the arm was broken.

1387
01:41:16,570 --> 01:41:17,832
That often happens.

1388
01:41:18,005 --> 01:41:20,496
Unfortunately,
what was a simple fracture then...

1389
01:41:20,674 --> 01:41:22,938
...has developed
into a serious complication now.

1390
01:41:23,110 --> 01:41:25,943
And it is serious.
He's had that injury for over a week.

1391
01:41:26,113 --> 01:41:29,310
- What are you doing for him, doctor?
- There's not much that I can do.

1392
01:41:29,483 --> 01:41:32,475
It calls for an operation
by someone who is an expert.

1393
01:41:32,653 --> 01:41:34,746
- Or else...
- or else what?

1394
01:41:34,922 --> 01:41:38,289
<i>Unless that boy is operated on
within the next few hours, I...</i>

1395
01:41:38,459 --> 01:41:40,552
Well, I can't be responsible for him.

1396
01:41:40,727 --> 01:41:42,820
Oh, no.

1397
01:41:43,497 --> 01:41:46,057
Well, we've got to do something.

1398
01:41:46,233 --> 01:41:49,293
You're right, son. I've phoned
the best orthopedic man I know.

1399
01:41:49,470 --> 01:41:51,665
Dr. Ganglin
at the General Hospital in Chicago.

1400
01:41:51,839 --> 01:41:54,740
But he's operating today,
and can't possibly get away.

1401
01:41:54,908 --> 01:41:56,876
That leaves us only one alternative.

1402
01:41:57,044 --> 01:41:58,773
We've got to get Willie to Chicago.

1403
01:41:58,946 --> 01:42:00,846
Well, all right, let's get him there.

1404
01:42:01,014 --> 01:42:03,915
Yes, get him there.
But we've got to get him there immediately.

1405
01:42:04,084 --> 01:42:07,349
- Well, couldn't we charter a plane?
- That would cost a lot of money.

1406
01:42:07,521 --> 01:42:09,785
I'm afraid Mrs. Brewster
could hardly afford that.

1407
01:42:10,190 --> 01:42:11,623
How much would it cost, doctor?

1408
01:42:11,792 --> 01:42:13,726
About $200.

1409
01:42:27,141 --> 01:42:29,507
Call the airport. We have the money.

1410
01:42:29,676 --> 01:42:32,167
- Two hundred dollars?
- Well, what are you waiting for?

1411
01:42:32,346 --> 01:42:35,804
- All right, I'll take care of it.
- Doctor, could we see Willie now, please?

1412
01:42:35,983 --> 01:42:38,383
Yes, I think you should.

1413
01:42:40,320 --> 01:42:42,686
Oh, Mrs. Brewster,
could I see you a moment?

1414
01:42:43,090 --> 01:42:45,058
Hello, shortstop.

1415
01:42:45,592 --> 01:42:48,618
I heard you. I'm not going.

1416
01:42:48,795 --> 01:42:50,490
Going where?

1417
01:42:50,664 --> 01:42:52,632
In that airplane.

1418
01:42:52,799 --> 01:42:55,393
Oh, but you've gotta go.

1419
01:42:56,837 --> 01:43:00,364
I know where you're getting the money.
And you're not gonna spend it on me.

1420
01:43:00,774 --> 01:43:02,139
What's money?

1421
01:43:02,309 --> 01:43:06,769
It's like corny saxophone players,
you can shake it out of trees.

1422
01:43:07,381 --> 01:43:10,373
Look, Willie, I'm your friend, aren't I?

1423
01:43:13,253 --> 01:43:17,189
- Yeah.
- And Jimmy's your friend too, isn't he?

1424
01:43:21,061 --> 01:43:22,426
Yeah.

1425
01:43:22,596 --> 01:43:27,158
Well, have we ever asked you to do
anything that wasn't good for you?

1426
01:43:28,635 --> 01:43:32,401
Look, Willie. Jimmy's a boss.

1427
01:43:32,573 --> 01:43:35,041
The only reason we've gotten
anywhere with the band...

1428
01:43:35,209 --> 01:43:37,507
...is because we've listened to him.

1429
01:43:37,678 --> 01:43:40,977
And everybody's always done
what he's asked us to.

1430
01:43:41,415 --> 01:43:43,542
Even hard things.

1431
01:43:43,884 --> 01:43:46,751
Things that we
sometimes didn't agree with.

1432
01:43:47,354 --> 01:43:49,686
But the only reason the band
has done anything...

1433
01:43:49,856 --> 01:43:52,825
<i>...the show and the play
and the dance...</i>

1434
01:43:52,993 --> 01:43:56,019
Well, those were little things.

1435
01:43:56,196 --> 01:43:59,165
And now, don't you see, Willie?

1436
01:43:59,333 --> 01:44:02,666
You're giving us a chance
to do a big thing.

1437
01:44:03,470 --> 01:44:08,271
Why, to Jimmy and me
and every person in the band...

1438
01:44:08,442 --> 01:44:12,071
...you're more important
than all the broadcasts in the world.

1439
01:44:12,246 --> 01:44:16,012
We've got the rest of our lives
to do broadcasts.

1440
01:44:17,184 --> 01:44:22,349
I know you'll do it because
I know you won't let us down.

1441
01:44:24,658 --> 01:44:27,991
You'll do it, won't you, Willie?

1442
01:44:31,398 --> 01:44:34,299
I always wanted to ride in an airplane.

1443
01:44:42,376 --> 01:44:44,537
- Mr. Connors is here, sir.
- Well, show him in.

1444
01:44:44,711 --> 01:44:48,613
- Yes, sir. This way, please.
- Thank you.

1445
01:44:49,716 --> 01:44:51,240
- Hello, Jimmy.
- Hello, Mr. Morgan.

1446
01:44:51,418 --> 01:44:53,750
- Breakfast?
- No, thanks. I don't care for anything.

1447
01:44:53,920 --> 01:44:55,512
- Well, sit down.
- Thank you, sir.

1448
01:44:55,689 --> 01:44:58,214
What time is that
Whiteman broadcast tonight?

1449
01:44:58,392 --> 01:44:59,984
Oh, 8:00.

1450
01:45:00,160 --> 01:45:02,526
Well, think you could win that contest?

1451
01:45:03,297 --> 01:45:05,595
I know we could, if we were there.

1452
01:45:06,433 --> 01:45:09,994
How long would it take you to get
your band together and get out of town?

1453
01:45:10,937 --> 01:45:12,529
Like that:

1454
01:45:12,706 --> 01:45:14,833
Well, that's too long.

1455
01:45:15,442 --> 01:45:18,900
There's a special train pulling into the yard
in three quarters of an hour.

1456
01:45:19,079 --> 01:45:21,479
I want you to be on it.

1457
01:45:22,783 --> 01:45:25,650
We'll be on it, Mr. Morgan.
But will it get us there in time?

1458
01:45:25,819 --> 01:45:29,687
Well, this train will. I've been
connected to that railroad for 20 years.

1459
01:45:29,856 --> 01:45:32,552
And this is the first time
I've ever had any fun out of it.

1460
01:45:32,726 --> 01:45:35,160
Now, get going and strike up the band.

1461
01:45:35,329 --> 01:45:39,288
Do you mean it? You ain't kidding us, huh?
Oh, thanks, Mr. Morgan.

1462
01:45:57,984 --> 01:46:01,852
Johnson, if you're looking for that pension,
you'd better get this train in on time.

1463
01:46:02,022 --> 01:46:04,820
Don't worry, Mr. Morgan.
This one's got to be in on time.

1464
01:46:04,991 --> 01:46:08,085
- Well, hello, everybody. Here we are.
- Hurry up. Hurry up, Barbara.

1465
01:46:08,261 --> 01:46:09,626
- Goodbye.
- Goodbye, my dear.

1466
01:46:09,796 --> 01:46:12,060
Hurry up. Hurry up, Barbara.
Well, here we go.

1467
01:46:12,232 --> 01:46:14,598
- Goodbye now. Good luck, my boy.
- Goodbye.

1468
01:46:14,768 --> 01:46:16,258
Goodbye.

1469
01:46:16,436 --> 01:46:18,495
Hurry up, Mary. Well, goodbye, Mom.

1470
01:46:18,672 --> 01:46:21,573
- Do you think we're gonna be the best?
- Everybody thinks so.

1471
01:46:21,742 --> 01:46:23,767
I don't know.
Everybody will be listening in.

1472
01:46:23,944 --> 01:46:26,845
- New York, Chicago, all over.
- They all came from Riverwood.

1473
01:46:27,013 --> 01:46:30,176
- Yeah.
- Anyway, I think you're the best.

1474
01:46:30,350 --> 01:46:34,081
And your father, he'd be so proud of you.

1475
01:46:34,488 --> 01:46:36,217
Well, then we're gonna win.

1476
01:46:36,390 --> 01:46:38,824
- You know what, Mom?
- What, Jimmy?

1477
01:46:39,393 --> 01:46:41,623
I'm gonna make you a queen.

1478
01:46:42,863 --> 01:46:46,060
- Goodbye. Goodbye, everybody.
- Goodbye.

1479
01:46:49,202 --> 01:46:50,760
Goodbye, Jimmy.

1480
01:46:55,041 --> 01:46:56,702
Good luck.

1481
01:47:56,670 --> 01:47:58,467
Time's about up. Three seconds to go.

1482
01:47:58,638 --> 01:47:59,866
- Are you ready?
- Almost.

1483
01:48:00,040 --> 01:48:02,565
- That's it.
- There you are.

1484
01:48:03,276 --> 01:48:05,369
Connect me with the stage.
I have the winner.

1485
01:48:05,545 --> 01:48:07,979
Come on, girls. You can see from here.

1486
01:48:19,860 --> 01:48:21,987
Thank you ladies and gentlemen
for listening...

1487
01:48:22,162 --> 01:48:23,959
...and for your wonderful reaction.

1488
01:48:24,130 --> 01:48:27,190
I'd also like to thank you for your votes
by phone and telegram...

1489
01:48:27,367 --> 01:48:28,834
...from all parts of the nation.

1490
01:48:29,002 --> 01:48:31,334
Which helped us pick
the winner of this contest.

1491
01:48:31,505 --> 01:48:35,441
Which only goes to prove that this country
not only has a genuine love for music...

1492
01:48:35,609 --> 01:48:38,203
...but is happy to acclaim
the youth of America.

1493
01:48:38,378 --> 01:48:40,972
This wonderful enthusiasm
and fine musicianship...

1494
01:48:41,147 --> 01:48:44,207
...demonstrated here tonight
makes me feel quite safe in saying...

1495
01:48:44,384 --> 01:48:47,717
...that we need have no fear
for the future of American music.

1496
01:48:47,888 --> 01:48:51,654
And now for the winner, a name you're
probably hearing for the first time tonight.

1497
01:48:51,825 --> 01:48:54,419
But which may in the future
become a musical byword.

1498
01:48:54,594 --> 01:48:57,256
Jimmy Connors and his band.

1499
01:49:06,773 --> 01:49:09,401
Thank you. Thank you.

1500
01:49:11,077 --> 01:49:13,671
- Jimmy, it's wonderful.
- Gosh, aren't you thrilled, Mary?

1501
01:49:13,847 --> 01:49:15,474
Thank you.

1502
01:49:16,049 --> 01:49:17,744
- Here. It's for you.
- Me?

1503
01:49:17,918 --> 01:49:19,886
Oh, Jimmy.

1504
01:49:24,424 --> 01:49:26,449
And now for our final number...

1505
01:49:26,626 --> 01:49:31,393
...performed by a combination of all
our contesting bands and glee clubs.

1506
01:49:31,565 --> 01:49:35,262
The honor of leading this finale
goes to our young winner, Jimmy Connors.

1507
01:49:35,435 --> 01:49:39,201
I feel pretty sure Jimmy's got a few tricks
up his sleeve he hasn't told me about.

1508
01:49:39,372 --> 01:49:42,068
- Maybe.
- Mr. Connors, the stick.

1509
01:49:42,242 --> 01:49:44,176
Thank you, Mr. Whiteman.

1510
01:49:52,752 --> 01:49:54,583
<i>Ladies and gentlemen...</i>

1511
01:49:55,322 --> 01:49:57,984
Well, I guess this is it.

1512
01:49:58,658 --> 01:50:00,785
I don't have to tell you how I feel.

1513
01:50:00,961 --> 01:50:04,192
If I felt any better,
gosh, I couldn't stand it.

1514
01:50:05,031 --> 01:50:08,125
When something wonderful like this
happens to anybody...

1515
01:50:08,301 --> 01:50:10,963
...I suppose you ought
to thank somebody.

1516
01:50:11,137 --> 01:50:14,436
They're not here,
but I know they're listening in.

1517
01:50:16,443 --> 01:50:21,005
Mr. Judd, I was all wrong about you.

1518
01:50:21,181 --> 01:50:24,014
You'll always be a swell guy
with us because you said:

1519
01:50:24,184 --> 01:50:26,277
"I'll buy the first ticket."

1520
01:50:28,455 --> 01:50:32,516
And as for you, Willie, you little shortstop,
even though you're in love with my girl...

1521
01:50:32,692 --> 01:50:35,525
...we're all thinking about you
and we want you to hurry up...

1522
01:50:35,695 --> 01:50:38,357
...and get out of bed
because we all need you.

1523
01:50:39,899 --> 01:50:42,299
And of all the people
throughout the United States...

1524
01:50:42,469 --> 01:50:44,994
...who might be listening
to this program...

1525
01:50:45,171 --> 01:50:47,765
...there's only one thing I'd like to say.

1526
01:50:47,941 --> 01:50:50,569
To the most important one of all.

1527
01:50:52,479 --> 01:50:53,946
Mom.

1528
01:50:55,448 --> 01:50:58,975
I don't know what I was thinking about
when I said that someday...

1529
01:50:59,152 --> 01:51:01,143
...l'd make you a queen.

1530
01:51:01,488 --> 01:51:05,219
Because if you hadn't been
a queen all the time...

1531
01:51:05,725 --> 01:51:07,784
...l'd never be here now.

1532
01:51:08,795 --> 01:51:13,192
Well, here it comes, Mom.

1533
01:52:57,337 --> 01:53:00,329
<i>We must have music in the land</i>

1534
01:53:01,040 --> 01:53:04,066
<i>For everybody loves a band</i>

1535
01:53:04,711 --> 01:53:08,306
<i>A good old rousing melody
Is a joy and inspiration</i>

1536
01:53:08,481 --> 01:53:12,076
<i>A hundred million folks agree
That a tune can stir a nation</i>

1537
01:53:12,252 --> 01:53:15,278
<i>So, music master, take command</i>

1538
01:53:15,955 --> 01:53:22,451
<i>Our hearts will beat to beat the band</i>

1539
01:53:23,129 --> 01:53:26,758
<i>Let the drums roll out
Let the trumpet call</i>

1540
01:53:26,933 --> 01:53:28,366
<i>- While the people shout
- Hooray!</i>

1541
01:53:28,535 --> 01:53:30,400
<i>Strike up the band</i>

1542
01:53:30,570 --> 01:53:34,028
<i>Hear the cymbals ring
Calling one and all</i>

1543
01:53:34,207 --> 01:53:37,506
<i>To that happy swing
Strike up the band</i>

1544
01:53:37,677 --> 01:53:41,169
<i>Yankee doo doodle-oo, doodle-oo
We'll come through Yankee doo, doodle-oo.</i>

1545
01:53:41,347 --> 01:53:45,181
<i>For the red, white, and blue, doodle-oo
Lend a hand</i>

1546
01:53:45,351 --> 01:53:49,082
<i>With the flag unfurled
We can face the world</i>

1547
01:53:49,255 --> 01:53:54,318
<i>Hey, leader, strike up the band</i>

1548
01:53:54,494 --> 01:53:57,657
<i>Let the drums roll out</i>

1549
01:53:57,831 --> 01:54:01,232
<i>Let the trumpet call</i>

1550
01:54:01,401 --> 01:54:04,165
<i>While the people shout</i>

1551
01:54:04,337 --> 01:54:08,296
<i>Strike up the band</i>

1552
01:54:08,474 --> 01:54:11,637
<i>Hear the cymbals ring</i>

1553
01:54:11,811 --> 01:54:15,212
<i>Calling one and all</i>

1554
01:54:15,381 --> 01:54:18,145
<i>To that martial swing</i>

1555
01:54:18,318 --> 01:54:22,049
<i>Strike up the band</i>

1556
01:54:22,222 --> 01:54:25,521
<i>And we'll all give the cheer as we stand</i>

1557
01:54:25,692 --> 01:54:28,991
<i>To the man with the stick in his hand</i>

1558
01:54:29,162 --> 01:54:32,222
<i>He's the man whose command of the band</i>

1559
01:54:32,398 --> 01:54:36,528
<i>Makes the band grand</i>

1560
01:54:36,703 --> 01:54:40,332
<i>And you can't go wrong
With a happy song</i>

1561
01:54:40,506 --> 01:54:43,942
<i>Hey, leader</i>

1562
01:54:44,110 --> 01:54:47,876
<i>Say, leader</i>

1563
01:54:48,281 --> 01:54:53,913
<i>Hey, leader, strike up the band</i>

1564
01:54:59,559 --> 01:55:03,017
<i>Mister leader
We all want to dance, sir</i>

1565
01:55:03,196 --> 01:55:09,692
<i>Give our feet a chance, sir
And say you'll play the La Conga</i>

1566
01:55:57,350 --> 01:56:00,114
<i>Rhythm is frantic</i>

1567
01:56:00,286 --> 01:56:03,050
<i>We feel romantic</i>

1568
01:56:03,222 --> 01:56:08,660
<i>Play a song of love</i>

1569
01:56:10,830 --> 01:56:14,425
<i>Our love affair</i>

1570
01:56:14,600 --> 01:56:18,195
<i>Was meant to be</i>

1571
01:56:18,371 --> 01:56:21,863
<i>It's me for you, dear</i>

1572
01:56:22,041 --> 01:56:25,306
<i>And you for me</i>

1573
01:56:25,478 --> 01:56:28,311
<i>We'll fuss and quarrel</i>

1574
01:56:28,481 --> 01:56:31,882
<i>And tears start to brew</i>

1575
01:56:32,051 --> 01:56:35,145
<i>But after the tears</i>

1576
01:56:35,321 --> 01:56:40,623
<i>Our love will smile through</i>

1577
01:56:40,793 --> 01:56:46,629
<i>When youth has had</i>

1578
01:56:47,633 --> 01:56:53,469
<i>Its merry fling</i>

1579
01:56:54,874 --> 01:57:01,370
<i>We'll spend our evenings</i>

1580
01:57:02,749 --> 01:57:09,245
<i>Remembering</i>

1581
01:57:11,524 --> 01:57:17,622
<i>Two happy people</i>

1582
01:57:17,797 --> 01:57:23,565
